WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.160 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; Announcer: From the Library
of Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:14.100
&gt;&gt; Karen Lloyd: Good afternoon.

00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:17.070
I'm Karen Lloyd, a retired Army
Division Colonel and Director

00:00:17.070 --> 00:00:19.240
of the Veteran's
History Project.

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:22.500
Thank you for choosing to come
to our panel discussion on PTSD

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:26.150
and Veterans Correctional
Housing Units.

00:00:26.150 --> 00:00:29.160
It's the second in our
ongoing PTSD panel series

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:31.950
in collaboration with
the National Institute

00:00:31.950 --> 00:00:33.340
of Corrections.

00:00:33.340 --> 00:00:35.360
I'd especially like
to welcome the members

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:39.260
of the Justice Involved
Veterans Network in attendance

00:00:39.260 --> 00:00:43.120
and those watching online, a
group of industry professionals

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:46.020
who research and produce
recommendations on how

00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:48.940
to help veterans involved
in the justice system.

00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:51.750
It is the work they do
that makes these types

00:00:51.750 --> 00:00:54.770
of discussions possible
and so valuable.

00:00:54.770 --> 00:00:59.490
As an Army veteran, I know how
untreated PTSD can affect a

00:00:59.490 --> 00:01:00.790
veteran's life.

00:01:00.790 --> 00:01:02.840
Our partners at the
National Institute

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:07.590
of Corrections know all too well
how PTSD can create problems

00:01:07.590 --> 00:01:11.870
with reentry into [inaudible]
and how it can lead to run-ins

00:01:11.870 --> 00:01:16.080
with the law and entry into
the justice and prison systems.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:20.100
But as you'll learn today, it
doesn't have to be this way.

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:22.160
We've pulled together
several experts

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:25.880
who have seen firsthand
how treating PTSD

00:01:25.880 --> 00:01:28.900
and adding structure to
veteran inmates' lives

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:31.850
in the Veterans Correctional
Housing Units can break the

00:01:31.850 --> 00:01:35.100
cycle of crime and recidivism.

00:01:35.100 --> 00:01:37.860
This panel represents
just another example

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:40.310
of how the Veterans
History Project is working

00:01:40.310 --> 00:01:44.800
to illuminate the work done by
a wide variety of organizations

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:48.180
that focus on assisting our
veterans to move forward

00:01:48.180 --> 00:01:52.120
with their lives and further
enrich their life stories,

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:54.520
which we certainly hope
they then choose to donate

00:01:54.520 --> 00:01:58.990
to the library so others can
benefit from their experiences.

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:02.900
While we had hoped to
have Director Inch today,

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:07.080
he sent the next-best
thing, a marine.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:12.040
Our next speaker is Frank Lara
of the U.S. Bureau of Prisons.

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:16.260
Mr. Lara is a veteran of the
United States Marine Corp

00:02:16.260 --> 00:02:19.540
and is currently the Assistant
Director of Congressional --

00:02:19.540 --> 00:02:23.010
Correctional Programs Division.

00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:24.380
Frank Lara began his --

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:27.810
began his career as a
correctional officer

00:02:27.810 --> 00:02:31.180
in Seagoville, Texas, where
he rose through the ranks,

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:33.440
eventually being named Warden

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:36.880
at the Federal Correctional
Complex, Beaumont,

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:39.370
where he received the New
Warden of the Year Award

00:02:39.370 --> 00:02:41.400
from the Bureau of Prisons.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:45.060
In 2017, he became
the Assistant Director

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:47.470
of the Correctional
Programs Division.

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:51.510
So please, let -- help me
welcome Assistant Director Lara.

