United States Marine Corp

00:03:50.380 --> 00:03:55.810
for four years and exited the
Marine Corp as a corporal.

00:03:55.810 --> 00:03:57.110
I'm here on behalf of the --

00:03:57.110 --> 00:03:59.090
Mark Inch, Director of
the Bureau of Prisons,

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:02.400
and the 37,000 staff who serve
this agency and our country

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:06.150
at our 122 bureau
facilities nationwide.

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:08.720
Prior to assuming the
directorship, Mr. Inch served

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:11.840
as the Provost Marshal
General/Commanding General,

00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:14.930
Criminal Investigative Division
in Army Corrections Command,

00:04:14.930 --> 00:04:17.480
where he maintained the
Executive Management Oversight

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:19.820
of the Army Corrections System.

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:23.710
Every veteran, regardless
of when or where they served

00:04:23.710 --> 00:04:26.360
or for how long, gave
of themselves to ensure

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:29.250
that all Americans continue
to enjoy the freedoms

00:04:29.250 --> 00:04:33.080
and opportunities that are the
foundation of this country.

00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:36.510
I know firsthand some of
the challenges veterans face

00:04:36.510 --> 00:04:38.880
as a result of spending
time in places

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:42.390
and circumstances many
cannot even imagine.

00:04:42.390 --> 00:04:45.440
We are here today to
increase the awareness

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:47.810
about Post Traumatic
Stress Disorder.

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:51.400
Some of these men and women
who suffer from PTSD struggle

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:55.260
to adapt back into society after
having served their country.

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:59.140
PTSD can also contribute
to their involvement

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:01.420
in the justice system.

00:05:01.420 --> 00:05:04.420
Approximately 7%, or 200,000,

00:05:04.420 --> 00:05:06.620
of the 2.3 million
people incarcerated

00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:09.680
in our nation's jails and
prisons are men and women

00:05:09.680 --> 00:05:12.380
who have served in
the armed forces.

00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:14.800
The majority of these
individuals completed service

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:17.250
with an honorable discharge.

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:18.550
A significant portion

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:20.750
of the combat troops are
returning home affected

00:05:20.750 --> 00:05:24.740
by visible and invisible battle
scars, including high rates

00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:28.250
of PTSD and traumatic
brain injury,

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:31.580
as well as serious physical
mental -- serious wounds.

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:34.250
Some veterans return
home and struggle

00:05:34.250 --> 00:05:37.360
and find themselves using
substances, and others struggle

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:40.070
with various forms of
mental illness related

00:05:40.070 --> 00:05:41.970
to their deployments.

00:05:41.970 --> 00:05:44.860
All of these issues
may, in some cases,

00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:48.840
lead to justice system
involvement and incarceration.

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:51.570
Veteran-specific housing units

00:05:51.570 --> 00:05:54.280
in our correctional environments
promotes opportunities

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:57.300
to assist veterans in
preparation to return

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:00.770
to our communities with
the skills and confidence

00:06:00.770 --> 00:06:05.490
to be productive and
contributing members of society.

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:08.910
The Bureau of Prisons houses
nearly 11,000 veterans

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:11.880
nationwide across
our 122 facilities.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:13.320
The vast majority are male,

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:14.840
although we do have
a small number

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:16.140
of female veterans as well.

00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:20.210
We have an office devoted to
meeting the needs of the groups

00:06:20.210 --> 00:06:23.000
of special inmates
with specialized needs.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.920
In December of 2017, we formally
recognized the inmate veterans

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:29.310
as a special population.

00:06:29.310 --> 00:06:32.580
We have a wide variety of
services for veteran inmates,

00:06:32.580 --> 00:06:34.150
but we are in the process

00:06:34.150 --> 00:06:35.920
of standardizing
services nationwide.

00:06:35.920 --> 00:06:40.500
We have developed a three-tiered
services delivery model.

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:44.590
Tier I services have just begun
to be rolled out nationwide.

00:06:44.590 --> 00:06:46.530
These will be available
at all facilities

00:06:46.530 --> 00:06:49.370
and are primarily
self-service in nature.

00:06:49.370 --> 00:06:53.090
They include training, best
practices, guidance from --

00:06:53.090 --> 00:06:56.160
guidance for staff, and forms
and resources that are available

00:06:56.160 --> 00:06:58.100
to the inmate population.

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:00.530
Each facility will
collaborate with veterans

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:03.340
and administration staff
to ensure inmate veterans

00:07:03.340 --> 00:07:05.330
and families of veterans
have access

00:07:05.330 --> 00:07:08.230
to the benefits information
they need.

00:07:08.230 --> 00:07:11.240
Tier II programs will be
rolled out later this year,

00:07:11.240 --> 00:07:13.940
and these are outpatient
services.

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:16.310
These will be delivered
in a group model

00:07:16.310 --> 00:07:18.700
and include a veteran
support group

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:20.940
and a veteran fitness group.

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:25.280
Finally, Tier III services will
be the most intense in nature

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:26.740
and will include piloting --

00:07:26.740 --> 00:07:28.040
will include the piloting

00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:30.990
of a unit-based residential
program using a therapeutic

00:07:30.990 --> 00:07:33.000
community model.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.920
We look forward to collaborating
with many of you as we roll

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:38.220
out these services nationwide.

00:07:44.330 --> 00:07:48.210
Today, it is my honor
and pleasure

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:49.880
to announce the National
Institute

00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:55.260
of Corrections Publication
entitled "Barracks Behind Bars".

00:07:55.260 --> 00:07:56.930
In veteran-specific
housing units,

00:07:56.930 --> 00:07:59.940
veterans help veterans
help themselves.

00:07:59.940 --> 00:08:03.790
This publication tells
the stories of both --

00:08:03.790 --> 00:08:05.720
of both some forward-thinking
sheriffs

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:08.620
who have instituted
veteran-specific housing units

00:08:08.620 --> 00:08:11.160
in their jails and from
some of the inmates

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:14.080
who have benefitted
from these programs.

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:17.330
We are seeing a number of
these housing units, dorms,

00:08:17.330 --> 00:08:21.260
or pods for veterans being
implemented across the country.

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:24.220
This publication is designed
to serve as a resource

00:08:24.220 --> 00:08:27.600
for the field as
jurisdictions consider

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:30.390
veteran-specific programming.

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:33.390
Another great resource of this
publication is the sequential

00:08:33.390 --> 00:08:35.860
intercept model that was adapted

00:08:35.860 --> 00:08:38.910
to the justice-involved
veteran population.

00:08:38.910 --> 00:08:43.140
As you can see, each decision
point provides resources

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:45.930
and represents an
opportunity to intervene

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:47.330
at the lowest level possible

00:08:47.330 --> 00:08:50.070
to minimize the collateral
consequences

00:08:50.070 --> 00:08:53.970
of a veteran getting more deeply
involved in the justice system.

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:00.240
Today, you will hear from
some of the folks featured

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:03.490
in the publication,
including our next speaker,

00:09:03.490 --> 00:09:09.080
Sheriff Peter Koutoujian, from
Middlesex County, Massachusetts.

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:12.170
He is the -- he is serving
his second elected term

00:09:12.170 --> 00:09:17.620
in the county with a population
of almost 6.1 million citizens,

00:09:17.620 --> 00:09:19.890
the largest county
in Massachusetts,

00:09:19.890 --> 00:09:23.740
and if I'm not mistaken,
in all of New England.

00:09:23.740 --> 00:09:26.560
His focus has been developing
a series of initiatives aimed

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:29.590
at increasing public confidence,

00:09:29.590 --> 00:09:31.770
providing a safer working
environment for staff,

00:09:31.770 --> 00:09:36.900
and improving the lives of
those in the county's custody,

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:40.560
including in 2016, the
creation of the HUMV Program,

00:09:40.560 --> 00:09:43.850
a housing unit for
military veterans.

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:46.510
Ladies and gentlemen,
Sheriff Peter Koutoujian.

