00:11:19.790 --> 00:11:22.540
While I did not serve
in the military,

00:11:22.540 --> 00:11:24.950
my family has a history
of service

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:27.100
that has always impacted me.

00:11:27.100 --> 00:11:28.670
My grandparents came
to this country

00:11:28.670 --> 00:11:31.270
to flee the Armenian genocide.

00:11:31.270 --> 00:11:32.660
They sought refuge
and opportunity

00:11:32.660 --> 00:11:34.070
in this country,
and they found it.

00:11:34.070 --> 00:11:37.030
Three of their sons
wore the uniform,

00:11:37.030 --> 00:11:38.620
including my Uncle Jack,

00:11:38.620 --> 00:11:40.980
who went on to become the
Veterans Service Agent

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:43.550
in my hometown of
Waltham, Massachusetts.

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:46.220
My Uncle Arson, who died in
an accident while serving

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:48.810
in the Philippines
at the age of 19.

00:11:48.810 --> 00:11:52.410
My grandmother, who could
barely speak English,

00:11:52.410 --> 00:11:55.340
was perhaps not technically,
but for all intents

00:11:55.340 --> 00:12:00.090
and purposes a gold-star mother
in the loss of her young son.

00:12:00.090 --> 00:12:02.360
And yet, my grandparents
loved this country

00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:06.280
and everything it afforded
us, the truest of patriots.

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:11.090
And I can just take a
moment to just think

00:12:11.090 --> 00:12:12.390
that how proud they
would be to know

00:12:12.390 --> 00:12:13.950
that their grandson was
speaking at the Library

00:12:13.950 --> 00:12:16.230
of Congress as well, right?

00:12:16.230 --> 00:12:19.090
It was that appreciation for
their service that made me want

00:12:19.090 --> 00:12:21.580
to do better for
incarcerated veterans.

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:24.580
After becoming sheriff
in 2011, I discovered

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:28.040
that we were lacking in
verified demographic information

00:12:28.040 --> 00:12:29.660
on veterans.

00:12:29.660 --> 00:12:33.530
At the time, the only way we
knew if someone was a veteran,

00:12:33.530 --> 00:12:35.680
if they told us they
were a veteran.

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:37.670
And so, when we spoke
about the problem

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:39.940
of incarcerated military
veterans across this country,

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:43.070
we really didn't have an
idea truly about the scope

00:12:43.070 --> 00:12:46.300
of this problem because we
didn't have verified numbers

00:12:46.300 --> 00:12:48.590
anywhere across this country.

00:12:48.590 --> 00:12:50.100
This was incredibly ineffective,

00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:51.540
and we knew that
we would miss folks

00:12:51.540 --> 00:12:53.880
because sometimes we wouldn't
know that they were in there

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:57.120
or as they were coming closer to
release, they would let us know,

00:12:57.120 --> 00:12:58.420
but by then it was too late

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:00.470
to give them the proper
programming while inside

00:13:00.470 --> 00:13:03.720
or the proper handoff to the
supports that they needed.

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:05.020
We later learned
that the reasons

00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:08.250
that many were not
identifying themselves,

00:13:08.250 --> 00:13:10.610
they were afraid
of losing benefits.

00:13:10.610 --> 00:13:12.690
Some didn't realize they
were qualified as a veteran.

00:13:12.690 --> 00:13:15.620
For some, it was either
stigma or shame at having been

00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:16.920
at a place of incarceration.

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:18.290
I knew there was a lot
more we could be doing

00:13:18.290 --> 00:13:20.900
to improve the lives
of these individuals

00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:23.960
and their families
-- and their families

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:26.720
and became personally
committed to this endeavor.

00:13:26.720 --> 00:13:29.600
It was at that point we
started speaking to the VA

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:32.940
about how we could better
identify veterans, and it began

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:35.870
with a launch of the Veterans
Reentry Search Service,

00:13:35.870 --> 00:13:37.520
or VRSS, developed by the VA.

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:41.250
The system allowed us to
match our lists of those

00:13:41.250 --> 00:13:44.090
in our custody against
the federal databases.

00:13:44.090 --> 00:13:47.170
And on day one, we had
19 men in our facility

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:50.610
who had self-identified at
having served this country.

00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:54.690
But VRSS immediately told us
that that number was wrong.

00:13:54.690 --> 00:13:57.330
We had another 44 in
our care, custody,

00:13:57.330 --> 00:13:58.630
and control that we
didn't know about,

00:13:58.630 --> 00:14:00.090
bring out total number to 63.

00:14:00.090 --> 00:14:01.980
In fact, two-thirds
more that we knew

00:14:01.980 --> 00:14:04.080
about were serving time with us.

00:14:04.080 --> 00:14:06.420
In this instant, we learned
that we had tripled the number

00:14:06.420 --> 00:14:09.360
of our veterans in our
custody, and that's why VRSS is

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:12.620
such a critical tool and
one I should be utilized --

00:14:12.620 --> 00:14:13.920
I believe should be utilized

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:16.300
by every correctional
facility across this country.

00:14:16.300 --> 00:14:18.810
That discovery eventually led to
the creation of the Housing Unit

00:14:18.810 --> 00:14:21.800
for Military Veterans, or
HUMV, designed in collaboration

00:14:21.800 --> 00:14:24.150
with administrators and staff

00:14:24.150 --> 00:14:26.730
and the incarcerated
veterans themselves.

00:14:26.730 --> 00:14:28.790
The unit was opened
in January of '16.

00:14:28.790 --> 00:14:32.450
It's been open for just about
2 1/2 years, and it was named

00:14:32.450 --> 00:14:34.650
by the veterans themselves.

00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:37.100
Ours is not the first, and it
certainly won't be the last,

00:14:37.100 --> 00:14:39.740
unit designed for
veterans suffering

00:14:39.740 --> 00:14:44.510
from so many ailments,
including PTSD.

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:46.700
Because sheriffs and other
correctional leaders from Albany

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:50.590
to Arizona to recognize
specially tailored programming

00:14:50.590 --> 00:14:54.620
for targeted population
works, a unique population,

00:14:54.620 --> 00:14:58.240
a unique solution,
unique results.

00:14:58.240 --> 00:15:00.020
In veterans' units
in particularly work

00:15:00.020 --> 00:15:03.610
so much more effectively
for a number of reasons.

00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:06.810
One, because of the staffs of
the officers, the volunteers

00:15:06.810 --> 00:15:09.910
and the programmatic staff who
are specially trained to work

00:15:09.910 --> 00:15:13.140
with veterans, the fact that
there are community resources

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:14.790
that can transition
to post release

00:15:14.790 --> 00:15:16.090
to continue the treatment,

00:15:16.090 --> 00:15:17.600
including the VA
any many nonprofits,

00:15:17.600 --> 00:15:21.370
and most importantly, because
of the veterans themselves,

00:15:21.370 --> 00:15:24.170
their own drive,
their own change.

00:15:24.170 --> 00:15:26.940
In Middlesex, we found
that the simple act

00:15:26.940 --> 00:15:28.800
of housing the veterans
together opened new doors

00:15:28.800 --> 00:15:31.790
for treatment and
rehabilitation.

00:15:31.790 --> 00:15:34.620
The men who have gone through
our HUMV have told us that being

00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:35.920
out of the general population

00:15:35.920 --> 00:15:39.300
and among other veterans allow
them to let their guard down,

00:15:39.300 --> 00:15:41.800
show them that they're not
alone, because they felt

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:44.580
so isolated and alone
before, and allow them to open

00:15:44.580 --> 00:15:46.430
up about their trauma
and other issues that led

00:15:46.430 --> 00:15:47.840
to their incarceration,

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:49.830
making it a truly
therapeutic community.

00:15:49.830 --> 00:15:52.420
In fact, it was said that it
was very much like being back

00:15:52.420 --> 00:15:54.310
in the service, where
in other parts

00:15:54.310 --> 00:15:56.950
of the correctional facility,
you had to watch your back,

00:15:56.950 --> 00:16:02.590
and in this unit, you knew that
you had someone at your back,

00:16:02.590 --> 00:16:05.740
and you had someone at your
left, and you had someone

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:09.800
at your right, and all you
needed to do was look forward.

00:16:11.050 --> 00:16:12.900
In our unit, it didn't
matter whether you had served

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:15.990
in Vietnam or Enduring Freedom,
whether you had spent a year

00:16:15.990 --> 00:16:18.530
on a submarine, you
were involved in combat,

00:16:18.530 --> 00:16:21.000
or you served stateside,

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.740
or you were discharged
honorably or not.

00:16:23.740 --> 00:16:25.940
And in some instances,
the issues that led

00:16:25.940 --> 00:16:29.350
to a less-than-honorable
discharge are the very same

00:16:29.350 --> 00:16:32.230
reasons that led to our
incarceration as well.

00:16:32.230 --> 00:16:34.910
If you swore an oath and were
willing to protect our freedom,

00:16:34.910 --> 00:16:37.020
we will consider
you for our program.

00:16:37.020 --> 00:16:40.640
Our experience is not that much
different from our colleagues

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:43.000
around the nation, many of
whom are here today and spoke

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:46.780
with such passion and
knowledge and expertise.

00:16:46.780 --> 00:16:49.570
The work that keeps happening
in these units is changing lives

00:16:49.570 --> 00:16:52.010
and changing families
and changing communities

00:16:52.010 --> 00:16:53.760
and making our communities safer

00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:57.490
and saving our communities
money, all at the same time.

00:16:57.490 --> 00:17:01.500
You can see in the data our own
snapshot pegged our recidivism

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:06.120
at just 5% for all those that
spent a minimum of 30 days

00:17:06.120 --> 00:17:10.400
in our custody over two
and a half years, 5%.

00:17:10.400 --> 00:17:14.660
Not only that, we have a
parole rate of about 95%.

00:17:14.660 --> 00:17:16.060
We had a number of
revising roles,

00:17:16.060 --> 00:17:18.690
meaning that the sentence
given was actually lessened

00:17:18.690 --> 00:17:21.690
by the courts themselves.

00:17:21.690 --> 00:17:23.290
We had a number of
men that were sent --

00:17:23.290 --> 00:17:26.770
that were able to remain in
our unit instead of going

00:17:26.770 --> 00:17:28.650
to the state prison
system because of the work

00:17:28.650 --> 00:17:30.490
that we had done with them
and the believe in the courts

00:17:30.490 --> 00:17:34.380
in our program, and
countless referrals

00:17:34.380 --> 00:17:36.600
to veterans' treatment courts.

00:17:36.600 --> 00:17:39.100
That's consistent with
other programs like Albany

00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:41.680
and San Francisco, who had
publicly reported other

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:44.490
single-digit recidivism rates.

00:17:44.490 --> 00:17:46.970
So this is not something
that is unique to Middlesex.

00:17:46.970 --> 00:17:49.090
It is happening across
this country.

00:17:49.090 --> 00:17:51.480
And more importantly, you can
hear it in the voices and see it

00:17:51.480 --> 00:17:56.040
in the stories of the veterans
themselves, veterans like Mike,

00:17:56.040 --> 00:17:58.690
who because of his participation
in one of these programs

00:17:58.690 --> 00:18:00.820
and our program was able
to get a revisor revoke

00:18:00.820 --> 00:18:02.120
and get out much earlier.

00:18:02.120 --> 00:18:06.190
I was walking at a Labor Day
parade waving at the people

00:18:06.190 --> 00:18:10.430
in the sides of the parade,
and suddenly out of the corner,

00:18:10.430 --> 00:18:12.600
as I walked by one
section up on a hill,

00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:15.930
I just could hear someone
yell out, "Humvee."

00:18:15.930 --> 00:18:19.710
And as I looked over, I saw a
man sitting there by a woman

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:21.060
on the hill with his thumb up.

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:22.720
And I ran -- thumb --
giving me a thumbs up.

00:18:22.720 --> 00:18:25.380
I ran up and it was Mike and he
was doing fabulously well and

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:26.680
yet we had allowed
him this opportunity.

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:31.910
Or John, who was two inches
short of killing himself

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:33.830
with a shotgun as
he said if he was --

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:35.760
if he had another two
inches of length in his arm,

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:37.590
he would have been dead.

00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:40.730
Came to our facility and
progressed so significantly

00:18:40.730 --> 00:18:46.070
that at one point, he was free
to leave on a parole to a bed

00:18:46.070 --> 00:18:47.780
that parole was providing
for him,

00:18:47.780 --> 00:18:49.570
but a bed that we were
going to provide him

00:18:49.570 --> 00:18:51.000
through Veterans
Affairs was not going

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.460
to be available for
another month.

00:18:54.480 --> 00:18:58.000
By God, he stayed with us
for another month in a place

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.430
of incarceration because he
knew he had a bed and a facility

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:02.480
that would be fitting
for his treatment

00:19:02.480 --> 00:19:05.810
and we had a bed following that
for the treatment of his PTSD.

00:19:05.810 --> 00:19:08.570
He stayed in jail an extra
month in this program.

00:19:08.570 --> 00:19:09.870
These are the stories
that you hear.

00:19:09.870 --> 00:19:12.880
Last year, the Washington
Examiner asked Pinal County

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:16.480
Sheriff Mark Lamb about the
idea of veteran's units popping

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:17.810
up across the country.

00:19:17.810 --> 00:19:20.550
Mark Lamb is a border sheriff.

00:19:20.550 --> 00:19:22.490
He is as true cowboy.

00:19:22.490 --> 00:19:27.680
He's a pretty amazing man
and a pretty amazing sheriff.

00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:31.940
In that, he talked about a visit
he made to our facility just

00:19:31.940 --> 00:19:34.030
to learn what we were doing
because he liked the idea.

00:19:34.030 --> 00:19:37.690
And this is a quote
from that newspaper.

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:39.150
It's kind of funny because we're

00:19:39.150 --> 00:19:41.580
like the odd couple,
said Sheriff Lamb.

00:19:41.580 --> 00:19:44.500
"He's a Democrat, liberal
from Massachusetts" --

00:19:44.500 --> 00:19:46.230
I'm not sure that was
meant in the most fond way

00:19:46.230 --> 00:19:50.780
down in Arizona -- "and I'm a
conservative, cowboy sheriff

00:19:50.780 --> 00:19:53.740
out of Arizona, but
together, as sheriffs,

00:19:53.740 --> 00:19:57.850
it shows how we work
together across this country."

00:19:57.850 --> 00:20:01.330
With these initiatives, we are
showing that veterans that,

00:20:01.330 --> 00:20:03.420
while they are being held
accountable for their actions,

00:20:03.420 --> 00:20:07.860
we also honor their service,
and as it is said in bridge

00:20:07.860 --> 00:20:11.190
of the military, we will
leave no man behind.

00:20:11.190 --> 00:20:14.680
We show them that we will
not leave them behind.

00:20:14.680 --> 00:20:18.630
Now, it's my honor to
