00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:50.990
Let me do a brief
personal account

00:23:50.990 --> 00:23:54.490
because I think some parts of
it are relevant to the subject

00:23:54.490 --> 00:23:56.690
that we're engaged in today.

00:23:56.690 --> 00:24:03.920
In the summer of 2005,
I made my first visit

00:24:03.920 --> 00:24:06.090
to Bethesda Naval Hospital.

00:24:06.090 --> 00:24:12.650
The previous November, I had
been very moved and troubled

00:24:12.650 --> 00:24:18.970
by the Battle of
Fallujah and Iraq.

00:24:18.970 --> 00:24:20.720
I thought about it a lot then.

00:24:20.720 --> 00:24:22.930
These were kids who
were the same age I was

00:24:22.930 --> 00:24:25.540
when I was in the Marines.

00:24:25.540 --> 00:24:29.260
These were the same age
of students that I saw

00:24:29.260 --> 00:24:33.050
on the campus of Dartmouth,
indeed the son of friends

00:24:33.050 --> 00:24:37.440
of ours and across the river
in Vermont had been killed

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:40.910
in Fallujah, a local Marine.

00:24:40.910 --> 00:24:45.440
And I thought I wanted to
reach out in some way to those

00:24:45.440 --> 00:24:49.590
who were serving and a good
friend, a retired marine, said,

00:24:49.590 --> 00:24:52.190
"Why don't you go down to
Bethesda Hospital and visit

00:24:52.190 --> 00:24:53.490
with the Marines there?"

00:24:53.490 --> 00:25:00.250
I did in the summer of
2005 and since then,

00:25:00.250 --> 00:25:04.740
I've been to Bethesda,
Walter Reed over 30 times

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:06.720
to visit with veterans.

00:25:06.720 --> 00:25:08.530
I haven't been there
for a few years.

00:25:08.530 --> 00:25:10.470
There are not as many.

00:25:10.470 --> 00:25:14.410
The wounded veterans pipeline
has slowed significantly.

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:18.670
When I would go to the
hospital on my pattern,

00:25:18.670 --> 00:25:19.970
it was always the same.

00:25:19.970 --> 00:25:22.510
I would go bed-to-bed

00:25:22.510 --> 00:25:25.650
and I would ask the
patient what happened.

00:25:25.650 --> 00:25:29.320
And, you know, I never once
encountered anyone and you --

00:25:29.320 --> 00:25:31.970
those of you who
know Walter Reed know

00:25:31.970 --> 00:25:34.290
that these were the
most seriously injured

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:36.150
and wounded in most cases.

00:25:36.150 --> 00:25:41.610
I never had anyone balk at
telling me what had happened.

00:25:41.610 --> 00:25:43.700
And then, I would engage
them in a conversation

00:25:43.700 --> 00:25:47.320
about their future - about
what they hoped to do

00:25:47.320 --> 00:25:48.620
and I kept reminding them,

00:25:48.620 --> 00:25:50.230
"You have a great
future ahead of you.

00:25:50.230 --> 00:25:54.320
Let's think about
what you might do."

00:25:54.320 --> 00:25:57.250
And I would ask them about
their own educational background

00:25:57.250 --> 00:25:58.550
and plans.

00:25:58.550 --> 00:25:59.850
And I would try to
encourage them

00:25:59.850 --> 00:26:01.840
to continue their education.

00:26:01.840 --> 00:26:06.730
I assured them that that already
demonstrated their discipline,

00:26:06.730 --> 00:26:10.320
their commitment to
serving and now they needed

00:26:10.320 --> 00:26:13.610
to prepare themselves for
the rest of their lives.

00:26:13.610 --> 00:26:16.310
They still had so much to do --

00:26:16.310 --> 00:26:19.260
so much more that
they could contribute.

00:26:19.260 --> 00:26:24.380
I was able to set up an
educational counseling program

00:26:24.380 --> 00:26:26.120
with the American
Council on Education

00:26:26.120 --> 00:26:27.550
at Walter Reed Bethesda.

00:26:27.550 --> 00:26:29.910
And I went out and
raised the money

00:26:29.910 --> 00:26:32.810
to get funded --
to get it started.

00:26:32.810 --> 00:26:37.400
And nearly 12 years
later, it is still in place

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:41.410
at Walter Reed now under
the Semper Fi Funds [assumed

00:26:41.410 --> 00:26:43.560
spelling] organizationally.

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:46.570
A few years after that,
I was able to work

00:26:46.570 --> 00:26:51.660
with Senators Jim Webb, and
John Warner, and Chuck Hagle

00:26:51.660 --> 00:26:53.610
on the post-9/11 GI bill.

00:26:53.610 --> 00:26:58.510
We had a meeting over at
the Senate office building

00:26:58.510 --> 00:27:02.860
in February of 2008.

00:27:02.860 --> 00:27:05.430
And I encouraged them
to be sure to include

00:27:05.430 --> 00:27:07.590
in that legislation
something that ended

00:27:07.590 --> 00:27:11.250
up being called the
Yellow Ribbon Program

00:27:11.250 --> 00:27:14.600
because that provided an
opportunity for private schools

00:27:14.600 --> 00:27:17.890
to contribute money of their
own to match that of the VA

00:27:17.890 --> 00:27:22.000
to make certain that private
schools were an option

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.180
for these veterans.

00:27:24.180 --> 00:27:25.700
And last year, the Congress

00:27:25.700 --> 00:27:29.120
with bipartisan anonymity
approved an extension

00:27:29.120 --> 00:27:31.950
and expansion of
that legislation.

00:27:31.950 --> 00:27:36.410
It was very important and I
think everyone needs to know --

00:27:36.410 --> 00:27:41.790
everyone needs to recognize --
that legislation such as this --

00:27:41.790 --> 00:27:43.700
legislation such as the G.I.

00:27:43.700 --> 00:27:49.710
bill, this is not a "Thank you
for your service" gratuity.

00:27:49.710 --> 00:27:55.610
It may provide an
incentive to serve.

00:27:55.610 --> 00:27:58.070
That would be good.

00:27:58.070 --> 00:28:01.630
It may provide immediately a
fully deserved acknowledgement

00:28:01.630 --> 00:28:05.130
of having done so
-- enabling veterans

00:28:05.130 --> 00:28:08.430
in their transitions
back to civilian life.

00:28:08.430 --> 00:28:12.880
But it is also an investment
in the future of this Republic.

00:28:12.880 --> 00:28:17.870
What a resource these
veterans can provide

00:28:17.870 --> 00:28:20.160
if we can enable them,
and encourage them,

00:28:20.160 --> 00:28:24.510
and provide them the
opportunity to pursue it.

00:28:24.510 --> 00:28:27.240
The ranks of the American
military today are filled

00:28:27.240 --> 00:28:29.940
with volunteers.

00:28:29.940 --> 00:28:34.860
They do not represent the
nation demographically.

00:28:34.860 --> 00:28:37.870
They tend to be more
rural than urban,

00:28:37.870 --> 00:28:41.160
more heartland than coastal.

00:28:41.160 --> 00:28:45.460
They're largely from blue
collar middle class backgrounds

00:28:45.460 --> 00:28:49.930
and they tend disproportionately
to come from military families.

00:28:49.930 --> 00:28:54.630
They constitute less than
one percent of the population

00:28:54.630 --> 00:29:01.510
and these 21st Century wars
are the first extended wars

00:29:01.510 --> 00:29:07.010
in American History with no
designated tax to help pay

00:29:07.010 --> 00:29:11.440
for the wars and no
service requirement

00:29:11.440 --> 00:29:14.320
for citizens of this country.

00:29:14.320 --> 00:29:20.120
So, much for George Washington's
reminder that it is necessary

00:29:20.120 --> 00:29:22.300
to go to -- if it is
necessary to go to war,

00:29:22.300 --> 00:29:27.990
all citizens should report
this with their treasure

00:29:27.990 --> 00:29:30.370
and with their service.

00:29:30.370 --> 00:29:35.460
Not anymore, not for these wars.

00:29:35.460 --> 00:29:39.730
These veterans can come home and
spend a good part of the rest

00:29:39.730 --> 00:29:42.410
of their lives helping to
pay off the debt of the wars

00:29:42.410 --> 00:29:45.640
in which they thought
and the vast majority

00:29:45.640 --> 00:29:49.330
of us go on with our lives.

00:29:49.330 --> 00:29:53.850
Those who serve in these 21st
Century wars are the best

00:29:53.850 --> 00:29:56.580
educated of Americans
to serve in any war.

00:29:56.580 --> 00:30:00.040
They are better educated than
their age group as a whole.

00:30:00.040 --> 00:30:05.320
The Armed Forces expect at
least a high school education

00:30:05.320 --> 00:30:08.750
and that's a good,
positive step.

00:30:08.750 --> 00:30:13.200
But, you know, we all know
unfortunately a high school

00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:19.520
education is insufficient
in this modern economy.

00:30:20.910 --> 00:30:24.780
The recent pattern of veterans
having higher unemployment rates

00:30:24.780 --> 00:30:28.060
than non-veterans has
been largely the result

00:30:28.060 --> 00:30:32.670
of their educational background
rather than a negative judgment

00:30:32.670 --> 00:30:34.690
on their military service.

00:30:34.690 --> 00:30:38.220
The parents and the grandparents

00:30:38.220 --> 00:30:42.970
of the current veterans came
home from World War II, Korea,

00:30:42.970 --> 00:30:47.020
Vietnam and if they
did not use the G.I.

00:30:47.020 --> 00:30:53.110
bill to pursue an education,
they could pretty much count

00:30:53.110 --> 00:31:00.350
on getting some good jobs at a
local factory, a mill or a mine.

00:31:00.350 --> 00:31:04.370
And they could really
count on knowing

00:31:04.370 --> 00:31:08.950
that if they worked hard,
they could probably have

00:31:08.950 --> 00:31:10.430
that job until they retired.

00:31:10.430 --> 00:31:15.040
And then, when they did retire,

00:31:15.040 --> 00:31:19.210
they would have some
pension plan to help them.

00:31:19.210 --> 00:31:21.250
Let's face it.

00:31:21.250 --> 00:31:24.180
Those opportunities are
far more limited today

00:31:24.180 --> 00:31:29.170
and there is far less likelihood
of that lifetime security.

00:31:29.170 --> 00:31:32.290
The Post 9/11 G.I.

00:31:32.290 --> 00:31:34.670
bill offers them an opportunity

00:31:34.670 --> 00:31:37.620
to set a course for
their future.

00:31:37.620 --> 00:31:43.240
But, you know, I learned
early on in my conversations

00:31:43.240 --> 00:31:46.890
that while it is essential to
provide the financial support

00:31:46.890 --> 00:31:51.450
for veterans to continue their
education, there was a prior --

00:31:51.450 --> 00:31:56.450
an often more difficult
counseling need and this was

00:31:56.450 --> 00:32:00.500
to encourage them to
do this, to assure them

00:32:00.500 --> 00:32:03.580
that they could do this.

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:09.640
While nearly all of those who've
joined the voluntary military

00:32:09.640 --> 00:32:12.500
may be high school graduates,

00:32:12.500 --> 00:32:17.020
most of them did not take
college preparatory courses.

00:32:17.020 --> 00:32:23.180
They probably have not taken
standardized ACT or SAT exams.

00:32:23.180 --> 00:32:27.240
They often feel unprepared
for higher education and some

00:32:27.240 --> 00:32:29.910
of them may not be ready.

00:32:29.910 --> 00:32:35.530
But I have no doubt that
they all can be ready.

00:32:35.530 --> 00:32:40.010
Counseling and convincing
them of this is essential

00:32:40.010 --> 00:32:42.850
as is follow-up support
to encourage them

00:32:42.850 --> 00:32:45.070
to pursue and to succeed.

00:32:45.070 --> 00:32:49.280
You see, we have
a national need --

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:53.080
an obligation to try to
encourage all students

00:32:53.080 --> 00:32:56.020
who have never been encouraged.

00:32:56.020 --> 00:32:58.520
They can do this.

00:32:58.520 --> 00:33:01.790
And this is where those
young men and women

00:33:01.790 --> 00:33:05.430
with military experience
can draw

00:33:05.430 --> 00:33:07.540
on some greater self-confidence

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:12.080
if we can remind them
why they should have this

00:33:12.080 --> 00:33:13.380
greater self-confidence.

00:33:13.380 --> 00:33:17.110
You know, there's another part

00:33:17.110 --> 00:33:18.850
of the American military
experience --

00:33:18.850 --> 00:33:21.380
of any military experience
that we need to understand.

00:33:21.380 --> 00:33:26.960
All of the children in
this country really --

00:33:26.960 --> 00:33:32.430
human beings across the
world learn as infants

00:33:32.430 --> 00:33:36.330
to remember two pretty
constant things.

00:33:36.330 --> 00:33:39.970
One is to lookout
for themselves.

00:33:39.970 --> 00:33:43.370
Avoid any threatening risks.

00:33:43.370 --> 00:33:45.900
Don't go there.

00:33:45.900 --> 00:33:48.220
Don't touch that.

00:33:48.220 --> 00:33:49.940
Look carefully.

00:33:49.940 --> 00:33:51.240
Be cautious.

00:33:51.240 --> 00:33:56.290
And they're also told
not to harm others

00:33:56.290 --> 00:33:59.490
and the latter is more
than parental guidance

00:33:59.490 --> 00:34:04.640
as it is emphasized under threat
of law, as well as moral code,

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:07.470
and religious teachers
teachings.

00:34:07.470 --> 00:34:11.890
Do not bring harm
to other people.

00:34:11.890 --> 00:34:15.020
Think of a very small
fraction of our citizens

00:34:15.020 --> 00:34:19.020
in their late teens
and early twenties.

00:34:19.020 --> 00:34:20.320
When they're mobilized
for war --

00:34:20.320 --> 00:34:22.080
[ Coughing ]

00:34:22.080 --> 00:34:23.380
-- they're told they have

00:34:23.380 --> 00:34:27.650
to suppress these fundamental
instincts and principles

00:34:27.650 --> 00:34:30.470
when the situation demands.

00:34:30.470 --> 00:34:33.620
They must be willing to put
themselves in harm's way

00:34:33.620 --> 00:34:35.400
without question or
without hesitation.

00:34:35.400 --> 00:34:37.790
[ Coughing ]

00:34:37.790 --> 00:34:39.090
"Go there and do it."

00:34:39.090 --> 00:34:41.440
They go and do.

00:34:41.440 --> 00:34:43.960
They don't stop and
reflect on it.

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:46.460
"This looks dangerous."

00:34:46.460 --> 00:34:47.760
That's not their job.

00:34:47.760 --> 00:34:50.100
They're told to go.

00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:54.260
And they must be willing
to bring harm to others --

00:34:54.260 --> 00:34:59.700
lethal harm without any
delay, any opportunity

00:34:59.700 --> 00:35:03.870
for moral reflection,
"Should I be doing this?"

00:35:03.870 --> 00:35:05.460
This is their assignment.

00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:11.370
Now when they return to civilian
life, they are told to return

00:35:11.370 --> 00:35:13.490
to their first rules --

00:35:13.490 --> 00:35:15.730
to forget that which they
have just learned and to wipe

00:35:15.730 --> 00:35:19.590
from their memory
contrary experiences.

00:35:19.590 --> 00:35:24.100
Obviously, in each of these
instances, this is impossible.

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:27.160
The vast majority of
combat veterans do return

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:32.630
to civilian lives successfully,
but they never forget

00:35:32.630 --> 00:35:37.100
that experience that they had.

00:35:37.100 --> 00:35:39.270
It's a difficult transition.

00:35:39.270 --> 00:35:44.370
Some do not return as
successfully as others.

00:35:44.370 --> 00:35:48.050
And indeed, some of
this group are a matter

00:35:48.050 --> 00:35:51.330
for our focus today.

00:35:51.330 --> 00:35:55.100
We need to know the
experience of war from those

00:35:55.100 --> 00:35:58.720
who were there before we can
begin to understand it --

00:35:58.720 --> 00:36:01.210
to know how profound
this experience is,

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:06.950
how contrary it is to everything
they've been taught and learned.

00:36:06.950 --> 00:36:12.720
As a Vietnam veteran,
army combat photographer,

00:36:12.720 --> 00:36:17.210
a friend Dick [inaudible]
recently described it.

00:36:17.210 --> 00:36:18.800
"They risk their lives.

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:20.700
They face terror.

00:36:20.700 --> 00:36:24.870
They lose buddies in battles
and then they come home

00:36:24.870 --> 00:36:28.160
where they have to square what
they had to do as warriors

00:36:28.160 --> 00:36:32.220
with what they are now expected
to do that they are home.

00:36:32.220 --> 00:36:34.520
It isn't easy."

00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:40.630
Veterans who are in prison for
committing a crime face many

00:36:40.630 --> 00:36:43.830
of the same problems
that non-veterans face

00:36:43.830 --> 00:36:45.290
in transitioning back

00:36:45.290 --> 00:36:48.690
to civilian life
following their release --

00:36:48.690 --> 00:36:52.530
problems of employment,
of acceptance,

00:36:52.530 --> 00:36:56.910
of reentering American society
while encountering suspicion

00:36:56.910 --> 00:36:59.040
at every turn.

00:36:59.040 --> 00:37:02.460
And finally, of avoiding
recidivism --

00:37:02.460 --> 00:37:09.810
this path is harder to avoid if
individuals encounter a society

00:37:09.810 --> 00:37:13.340
that has little confidence
and a good outcome.

00:37:14.530 --> 00:37:17.390
These problems may be
compounded for veterans

00:37:17.390 --> 00:37:19.120
who have been released.

00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:24.190
They confront dual and
reinforcing stereotypes.

00:37:24.190 --> 00:37:27.830
The current Ban the
Box initiative

00:37:27.830 --> 00:37:30.260
to encourage perspective
employers

00:37:30.260 --> 00:37:32.770
and college admissions
applications

00:37:32.770 --> 00:37:34.940
to discontinue asking questions

00:37:34.940 --> 00:37:40.800
about criminal convictions
is an interesting effort.

00:37:40.800 --> 00:37:46.120
It's reminiscent to me of
Vietnam veterans in the 1970's

00:37:46.120 --> 00:37:48.880
who came home and didn't
acknowledge their military

00:37:48.880 --> 00:37:52.210
service on job applications

00:37:52.210 --> 00:37:55.050
because they thought
this was something

00:37:55.050 --> 00:37:56.700
that would be far
better for them

00:37:56.700 --> 00:37:59.340
if their employer didn't have
to say, "Were you a veteran?

00:37:59.340 --> 00:38:00.640
Were you at [inaudible]?"

00:38:00.640 --> 00:38:06.150
and ask some of the most foolish
questions you could imagine.

00:38:06.150 --> 00:38:09.920
We've, we've come a
great distance medically

00:38:09.920 --> 00:38:12.930
since posttraumatic stress
disorder was recognized

00:38:12.930 --> 00:38:18.840
as a clinical disorder, but
that journey is not over,

00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:22.470
and the distance
remains even greater

00:38:22.470 --> 00:38:26.290
in accomplishing
social acceptance

00:38:26.290 --> 00:38:28.820
of this mental health condition.

00:38:28.820 --> 00:38:31.490
The mental, the medical
and the legal recognition

00:38:31.490 --> 00:38:34.650
of PTSD has been so important.

00:38:34.650 --> 00:38:37.380
We discuss is more openly now.

00:38:37.380 --> 00:38:41.620
But you know I also
worry that this talking

00:38:41.620 --> 00:38:48.010
about it more openly ironically
has buttressed another cruel

00:38:48.010 --> 00:38:54.310
stereotype, that of the
socially unhinged veteran.

00:38:54.310 --> 00:38:55.830
The Vietnam veterans

00:38:55.830 --> 00:39:01.740
in the 1970's came
straight into this headwind.

00:39:01.740 --> 00:39:05.470
And they encountered
movies such as Taxi Driver

00:39:05.470 --> 00:39:07.860
and Apocalypse Now,

00:39:07.860 --> 00:39:13.540
which deranged psychotic
veterans emerged.

00:39:13.540 --> 00:39:17.170
The 1970's were not kind
to veterans coming back

00:39:17.170 --> 00:39:19.310
from an unpopular war.

00:39:19.310 --> 00:39:23.000
In the 1970's on one episode

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:26.830
of the popular television
show Kojak,

00:39:26.830 --> 00:39:29.830
Telly Savalas confronted
a series

00:39:29.830 --> 00:39:33.470
of brutal homicides
in Manhattan.

00:39:33.470 --> 00:39:36.560
He told one of his
detectives to find

00:39:36.560 --> 00:39:39.630
out if there were
any Vietnam veterans

00:39:39.630 --> 00:39:42.370
in the neighborhood
of the crimes.

00:39:42.370 --> 00:39:44.460
Think of this.

00:39:44.460 --> 00:39:47.010
Are there any Vietnam
veterans there?

00:39:48.770 --> 00:39:53.860
PTSD is a companion of
all wars, redevises,

00:39:53.860 --> 00:39:58.510
but this was not
even done diagnosed

00:39:58.510 --> 00:40:01.570
as a clinical condition
until 1979.

00:40:01.570 --> 00:40:05.410
Before that, veterans with
problems were categorized

00:40:05.410 --> 00:40:08.140
as suffering from
the Vietnam syndrome,

00:40:08.140 --> 00:40:11.790
as if it were an
isolated condition of what

00:40:11.790 --> 00:40:13.280
so many other veterans thought

00:40:13.280 --> 00:40:17.610
of as this whining hippy group
coming back from Vietnam.

00:40:17.610 --> 00:40:24.100
World War II veterans, their
parents' generation told them

00:40:24.100 --> 00:40:26.510
to grow up and get over it.

00:40:26.510 --> 00:40:28.320
They said we did.

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:34.720
But of course, not
all of them did.

00:40:34.720 --> 00:40:40.130
It was called combat
fatigue or shell shock then.

00:40:40.130 --> 00:40:46.110
The Vietnam veterans spoke of
nightmares becoming day-mares.

00:40:46.110 --> 00:40:49.290
One said to me, if
those other people had

00:40:49.290 --> 00:40:53.490
to spend just one night inside
my nightmares they would fall

00:40:53.490 --> 00:40:57.030
to the floor with
tears in their eyes.

00:40:57.030 --> 00:41:00.580
But you know these
veterans endured

00:41:00.580 --> 00:41:05.220
and they have contributed so
much to our national life.

00:41:05.220 --> 00:41:08.480
One thing we've learned is
that veterans will speak

00:41:08.480 --> 00:41:11.140
about their experiences
more candidly and more,

00:41:11.140 --> 00:41:14.530
more personally with
other veterans.

00:41:14.530 --> 00:41:18.060
Some of the best counseling
sessions involve a group

00:41:18.060 --> 00:41:20.090
of veterans sharing
their stories

00:41:20.090 --> 00:41:22.190
and encouraging one another.

00:41:22.190 --> 00:41:26.300
If post-911 veterans
have not had to contend

00:41:26.300 --> 00:41:32.260
with the same nasty degrading
stereotypes in popular culture,

00:41:32.260 --> 00:41:36.460
they still have too often to
encounter wisps of the fear

00:41:36.460 --> 00:41:39.290
and prejudice that remain.

00:41:39.290 --> 00:41:42.890
And here they're reinforcing
fear and prejudice and suspicion

00:41:42.890 --> 00:41:47.120
that confronts the ones
where former convicts

00:41:47.120 --> 00:41:50.270
and veterans can be
even harder to escape.

00:41:50.270 --> 00:41:54.760
If this is their
difficult assignment,

00:41:54.760 --> 00:41:57.490
I have confidence in them.

00:41:57.490 --> 00:42:01.100
But our society has
a role as well.

00:42:01.100 --> 00:42:05.810
We still need to thank them for
their service and recognize this

00:42:05.810 --> 00:42:09.780
as not a condescending
throw-away gratuity.

00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:14.250
They need a hand, not a
handout, they need a hand.

00:42:14.250 --> 00:42:16.940
We need to recognize what
they did on our behalf,

00:42:16.940 --> 00:42:18.810
even if they have
stumbled since.

00:42:18.810 --> 00:42:21.050
They have much to offer.

00:42:21.050 --> 00:42:24.910
You know Americans today
do juggle their views

00:42:24.910 --> 00:42:28.130
of the current generation
of veterans.

00:42:28.130 --> 00:42:31.210
They applaud them when
they're introduced at events.

00:42:31.210 --> 00:42:35.000
They call them all heroes.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:40.810
And yet they're also
a little bit uneasy

00:42:40.810 --> 00:42:42.630
around them sometimes.

00:42:42.630 --> 00:42:46.260
We all need to know them better.

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:47.800
We need to understand
who they are,

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:50.340
what they've endured,
what they want to do.

00:42:50.340 --> 00:42:55.330
These veterans have worked
effectively with others

00:42:55.330 --> 00:42:57.950
of different backgrounds.

00:42:57.950 --> 00:43:01.660
They've assumed responsibility
and accountability.

00:43:01.660 --> 00:43:04.170
They function in
complex organizations

00:43:04.170 --> 00:43:07.910
and in an advanced
technological environment,

00:43:07.910 --> 00:43:11.090
and they've confronted dangerous
situations while respecting

00:43:11.090 --> 00:43:13.480
people of different cultures.

00:43:13.480 --> 00:43:16.600
They have learned
discipline and restrained

00:43:16.600 --> 00:43:19.780
in self-confidence
and tolerance.

00:43:19.780 --> 00:43:23.230
They have observed, and
they have themselves offered

00:43:23.230 --> 00:43:28.800
sacrifice for a greater good.

00:43:28.800 --> 00:43:32.720
I'm impressed by the options
that sheriffs and wardens

00:43:32.720 --> 00:43:35.820
such as those speaking
here today.

00:43:35.820 --> 00:43:39.990
Officers such as
Sheriff Peter Koutoujian

00:43:39.990 --> 00:43:42.820
and his Middlesex County team.

00:43:42.820 --> 00:43:47.340
Captain Malik Muhammad of
Orange County, Florida.

00:43:47.340 --> 00:43:50.720
