00:56:21.440 --> 00:56:23.880
Thank you.

00:56:23.880 --> 00:56:25.200
&gt;&gt; Michael Jackson: My
name is Michael Jackson,

00:56:25.200 --> 00:56:28.710
I'm from the Cleveland
area, and I'm a judge

00:56:28.710 --> 00:56:31.590
at [inaudible] County
[inaudible] court.

00:56:31.590 --> 00:56:35.440
I ran as a veteran and
was the only veteran,

00:56:35.440 --> 00:56:38.580
am presently the only
veteran on our bench.

00:56:38.580 --> 00:56:44.940
In the Vietnam War after my
college graduation I joined the

00:56:44.940 --> 00:56:48.600
Marine Corps and was a first
lieutenant commanding a company

00:56:48.600 --> 00:56:52.200
and a second lieutenant
commanding a platoon.

00:56:52.200 --> 00:56:55.220
Came back, went to law
school, married the love

00:56:55.220 --> 00:56:57.400
of my life who is here today.

00:56:57.400 --> 00:57:00.800
And practiced law and decided I
wanted to be a judge at the end

00:57:00.800 --> 00:57:02.100
of my career and I wanted

00:57:02.100 --> 00:57:03.850
to start a veterans'
treatment court.

00:57:03.850 --> 00:57:06.150
Three years ago, we had
one veteran and now we have

00:57:06.150 --> 00:57:09.320
over 100 veterans in my court.

00:57:09.320 --> 00:57:13.720
And we started a jail pod
connecting our veterans court

00:57:13.720 --> 00:57:16.440
with those in the county
jail and look forward

00:57:16.440 --> 00:57:20.250
to exchanging some of
those views this afternoon.

00:57:20.250 --> 00:57:22.190
&gt;&gt; Malik Muhammad: Good
afternoon I'm Malik Muhammad

00:57:22.190 --> 00:57:23.500
from Orlando, Florida.

00:57:23.500 --> 00:57:24.800
I'm currently employed

00:57:24.800 --> 00:57:26.790
by the Orange County Corrections
Department and I've been there

00:57:26.790 --> 00:57:28.580
for the last 19 years.

00:57:28.580 --> 00:57:32.200
I am retired military, I
retired in January of this year.

00:57:32.200 --> 00:57:35.010
The first six years of my
military career was spent

00:57:35.010 --> 00:57:37.260
on active duty, and
the remainder was spent

00:57:37.260 --> 00:57:40.220
as a reservist out
of Orlando, Florida.

00:57:40.220 --> 00:57:42.110
And on behalf of my
chief Corinda Riley

00:57:42.110 --> 00:57:44.320
and our Mayor Theresa
Jacobs I bring you greetings

00:57:44.320 --> 00:57:46.100
from Orange County
Corrections Department.

00:57:46.100 --> 00:57:51.640
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: I guess it's me.

00:57:51.640 --> 00:57:54.620
I'm Ron Perez, I
too was drafted.

00:57:54.620 --> 00:57:57.150
I'm a Vietnam veteran.

00:57:57.150 --> 00:58:00.490
I was drafted shortly after
high school, served in Vietnam

00:58:00.490 --> 00:58:07.100
from August 1, 1967
till August 1968.

00:58:07.100 --> 00:58:11.620
1975 I went into the San
Francisco county jail,

00:58:11.620 --> 00:58:13.830
and I've been there ever since,

00:58:13.830 --> 00:58:15.480
working for the sheriff
department

00:58:15.480 --> 00:58:18.400
in their prisoner services
division, developing

00:58:18.400 --> 00:58:21.290
and creating programs.

00:58:21.290 --> 00:58:24.800
I retired from the sheriff's
department approximately 2008.

00:58:24.800 --> 00:58:27.750
Shortly thereafter, they
contacted me and said, "Ron,

00:58:27.750 --> 00:58:31.610
remember that Veteran's Program
you said we should always start?

00:58:31.610 --> 00:58:32.910
Well, we're going to do it."

00:58:32.910 --> 00:58:36.400
So I came back on a consulting
basis and did development

00:58:36.400 --> 00:58:38.280
and implementation
of the program.

00:58:38.280 --> 00:58:41.090
We started out program in 2010,

00:58:41.090 --> 00:58:48.130
2013 because we had showed we
had a significant population,

00:58:48.130 --> 00:58:50.040
the veteran's court started.

00:58:50.040 --> 00:58:52.250
Our program is called COVER.

00:58:52.250 --> 00:58:56.880
COVER stands for Community of
Veterans Engaged in Restoration.

00:58:56.880 --> 00:58:59.180
That name was --

00:59:01.040 --> 00:59:05.600
-- was the idea at brain trial
of our veteran service officer,

00:59:05.600 --> 00:59:07.740
our sheriff at that time.

00:59:07.740 --> 00:59:10.580
Loved having programs
that had little --

00:59:10.580 --> 00:59:14.190
nice little tippets that went to
him like, sheriff work furlough,

00:59:14.190 --> 00:59:16.630
and sheriffs work
alternatives, so when he --

00:59:16.630 --> 00:59:18.510
and he loved restoring justice.

00:59:18.510 --> 00:59:21.760
And when he heard
community of veterans engaged

00:59:21.760 --> 00:59:24.580
in restoration, he loved it.

00:59:24.580 --> 00:59:27.650
Part of the reason
it was called COVER,

00:59:27.650 --> 00:59:32.280
the officer from veteran service
office was a retired air force

00:59:32.280 --> 00:59:36.490
military, and you all know,
if you were in the military,

00:59:36.490 --> 00:59:39.110
you can't leave billets
without your cover.

00:59:39.110 --> 00:59:40.610
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Good
to have you out here.

00:59:40.610 --> 00:59:43.090
If you're not familiar
with how --

00:59:43.090 --> 00:59:44.390
is anybody in the
room not familiar

00:59:44.390 --> 00:59:47.100
with how the correction
system works?

00:59:47.100 --> 00:59:49.010
Good. We don't have to
waste a lot of time.

00:59:49.010 --> 00:59:51.330
So you know when you're in the
corrections -- and I had --

00:59:51.330 --> 00:59:53.560
my wife worked at one
of worst -- it was --

00:59:53.560 --> 00:59:55.790
The New York Times dubbed it
the most violent institution

00:59:55.790 --> 00:59:57.720
for youthful offenders
in the free world.

00:59:57.720 --> 00:59:59.020
So I was really happy
when she'd [Inaudible]

00:59:59.020 --> 01:00:01.200
after work every day, there was
[Inaudible] out in California.

01:00:01.200 --> 01:00:03.520
And it was a absolutely
horrible place.

01:00:03.520 --> 01:00:07.320
Very well run, and immaculate,
I mean you'd look at it

01:00:07.320 --> 01:00:08.780
and think it was a
mall when you drove by.

01:00:08.780 --> 01:00:11.400
But when I went in and I
took a tour, I remembered

01:00:11.400 --> 01:00:13.040
that there were movements done

01:00:13.040 --> 01:00:14.820
from certain sections
of populations.

01:00:14.820 --> 01:00:17.850
They literally had to separate
the populations for fear

01:00:17.850 --> 01:00:19.150
that they would be violence.

01:00:19.150 --> 01:00:20.720
And they were all
pretty much high risk,

01:00:20.720 --> 01:00:22.090
because they said
anybody between 18

01:00:22.090 --> 01:00:25.710
and 25 was probably the
most violent, or most likely

01:00:25.710 --> 01:00:28.040
to offend in a population.

01:00:28.040 --> 01:00:30.680
And that's what we're talking
about with most of the veterans.

01:00:30.680 --> 01:00:32.410
We're talking that age group.

01:00:32.410 --> 01:00:34.320
So when they go into prison,

01:00:34.320 --> 01:00:36.510
you would think it would be a
no-brainer, that you'd segregate

01:00:36.510 --> 01:00:38.360
that population perhaps.

01:00:38.360 --> 01:00:39.660
And then you say
to yourself, "Well,

01:00:39.660 --> 01:00:42.440
why would they separate --
segregate that population?

01:00:42.440 --> 01:00:44.090
What is it about the
veterans population

01:00:44.090 --> 01:00:45.560
that needs segregating?"

01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:46.860
So let's put that to the panel.

01:00:46.860 --> 01:00:49.660
Why is it a good idea to
segregate the population

01:00:49.660 --> 01:00:52.440
of veterans that find
themselves incarcerated?

01:00:52.440 --> 01:00:56.390
What is it that's going to come
from that, is it productive?

01:00:56.390 --> 01:01:00.090
Is there a chance that perhaps
you'll put them on the path?

01:01:00.090 --> 01:01:02.890
What is the reason for
segregating that population?

01:01:02.890 --> 01:01:04.190
Anybody, please.

01:01:04.190 --> 01:01:05.610
&gt;&gt; Judge Michael E. Jackson:
Well, I think the basic reason

01:01:05.610 --> 01:01:09.620
for doing that is that there's
something about being a veteran

01:01:09.620 --> 01:01:13.850
that is different and separate
from those who have not served.

01:01:13.850 --> 01:01:16.510
And to place veterans together,

01:01:16.510 --> 01:01:20.520
you're recreating a
shared military experience.

01:01:20.520 --> 01:01:23.480
And from my experience, it
doesn't matter if the person was

01:01:23.480 --> 01:01:27.380
in combat or not, served
early or served late.

01:01:27.380 --> 01:01:31.100
But that shared military
experience.

01:01:31.100 --> 01:01:33.820
Other veterans understand.

01:01:33.820 --> 01:01:37.660
And the veterans in our county
jail say the same thing that all

01:01:37.660 --> 01:01:39.670
of the veterans in
the publication

01:01:39.670 --> 01:01:41.640
that you'll have the
opportunity to read,

01:01:41.640 --> 01:01:47.160
say in other jails throughout
the country, is that it's safer,

01:01:47.160 --> 01:01:52.160
it's quieter, it's more
peaceful, they don't fight.

01:01:52.160 --> 01:01:54.760
If they do, they
solve it themselves.

01:01:54.760 --> 01:01:58.280
And they respect
each other in a way

01:01:58.280 --> 01:02:00.140
that because they've all served.

01:02:00.140 --> 01:02:04.760
They may not like each other,
but they do respect each other

01:02:04.760 --> 01:02:06.490
because of that service.

01:02:06.490 --> 01:02:10.350
And they end up helping
each other in that regard.

01:02:10.350 --> 01:02:12.690
And for those who
have drug addictions,

01:02:12.690 --> 01:02:17.320
or mental health addictions
or issues, particularly PTSD,

01:02:17.320 --> 01:02:21.100
being in a quite safe place,
even if you have to be there

01:02:21.100 --> 01:02:26.060
in jail, is much better
than the general population.

01:02:26.060 --> 01:02:28.860
&gt;&gt; Greg Crawford: So I had -- I
went on a few of the site visits

01:02:28.860 --> 01:02:31.010
for this publication, and
I just want to kind of add

01:02:31.010 --> 01:02:32.630
to what he said, judge.

01:02:32.630 --> 01:02:37.430
Another really good thing for
this is the efficiency of it.

01:02:37.430 --> 01:02:40.060
One of the folks
mentioned, in king --

01:02:40.060 --> 01:02:42.850
in Seattle, was the fact

01:02:42.850 --> 01:02:45.990
that the VA could
come-in in one spot.

01:02:45.990 --> 01:02:48.150
People could come into one
spot and talk to people,

01:02:48.150 --> 01:02:49.830
rather than bounce
around the different parts

01:02:49.830 --> 01:02:51.240
of the correctional facility.

01:02:51.240 --> 01:02:54.140
So I think efficiency, and
having those resources all

01:02:54.140 --> 01:02:56.420
in one spot makes
a lot of sense.

01:02:56.420 --> 01:02:58.790
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: And it also
helps your outside agencies,

01:02:58.790 --> 01:03:01.520
and also it makes it easier
for them because they know

01:03:01.520 --> 01:03:04.130
that they just have
to visit one facility,

01:03:04.130 --> 01:03:07.020
and they know they can call
and check and make sure

01:03:07.020 --> 01:03:09.420
when they're coming out to
do the intake on the veteran,

01:03:09.420 --> 01:03:11.530
that the veteran is
there, not in court

01:03:11.530 --> 01:03:13.320
or being moved somewhere else.

01:03:13.320 --> 01:03:14.620
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Have
you spent a lot of time

01:03:14.620 --> 01:03:17.320
with the inmates that
represents this population?

01:03:17.320 --> 01:03:18.770
Do you get a sense
from some of them

01:03:18.770 --> 01:03:21.980
that they should have been
some sort of intervention?

01:03:21.980 --> 01:03:25.050
What I found from working with,
especially those who came back

01:03:25.050 --> 01:03:27.920
with PTSD, is that
a lot of times,

01:03:27.920 --> 01:03:29.500
they just needed a friend.

01:03:29.500 --> 01:03:32.460
A lot of times they come back
and they feel isolated, lost,

01:03:32.460 --> 01:03:34.340
they feel that language
that they learned overseas,

01:03:34.340 --> 01:03:35.640
they don't speak it anymore,

01:03:35.640 --> 01:03:36.940
nobody in their family
understands it,

01:03:36.940 --> 01:03:38.470
so they just shut down.

01:03:38.470 --> 01:03:40.260
Is that often times
what you find?

01:03:40.260 --> 01:03:42.370
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: We still have
a significant population

01:03:42.370 --> 01:03:45.220
of Vietnam air veterans
in our jails.

01:03:45.220 --> 01:03:47.830
And quite often, very often,

01:03:47.830 --> 01:03:49.600
they'll say this
is what I needed

01:03:49.600 --> 01:03:51.810
when I came home from veteran.

01:03:51.810 --> 01:03:55.250
Something like this I would
not have spent my entire life

01:03:55.250 --> 01:03:57.520
in the criminal justice system.

01:03:57.520 --> 01:03:58.820
&gt;&gt; Captain Malik Muhammad:
And I've heard similar stories

01:03:58.820 --> 01:04:01.040
in Orange County, we have
veterans that talk about,

01:04:01.040 --> 01:04:02.340
"If these programs
would have been

01:04:02.340 --> 01:04:04.140
around when they
first got out, maybe,

01:04:04.140 --> 01:04:05.440
just maybe they would
not have ended

01:04:05.440 --> 01:04:06.740
up in the criminal
justice system."

01:04:06.740 --> 01:04:08.920
So again, it's a benefit
of having them there,

01:04:08.920 --> 01:04:10.800
and I also believe
it starts to process.

01:04:10.800 --> 01:04:12.460
When you have those
veterans together.

01:04:12.460 --> 01:04:14.570
One of the things the military
taught us was comradery

01:04:14.570 --> 01:04:15.870
and the espirit de corps.

01:04:15.870 --> 01:04:18.710
So by placing all these guys
in one dedicated housing unit,

01:04:18.710 --> 01:04:21.460
you start that treatment
process for recovery.

01:04:21.460 --> 01:04:22.810
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Let's talk
about resource for a second,

01:04:22.810 --> 01:04:24.340
'cause everybody
is so keenly aware

01:04:24.340 --> 01:04:25.680
that everything cost money.

01:04:25.680 --> 01:04:27.740
This doesn't strike
me as any program,

01:04:27.740 --> 01:04:29.660
like I know the middle
six, sheriff was talking

01:04:29.660 --> 01:04:31.170
about the kinds of
things that they've done.

01:04:31.170 --> 01:04:34.380
This is just redirecting,
as opposed to trying

01:04:34.380 --> 01:04:36.140
to acquire more money
or a budget

01:04:36.140 --> 01:04:37.440
to put something together.

01:04:37.440 --> 01:04:38.820
This is just about
redirecting resources, right?

01:04:38.820 --> 01:04:41.050
This isn't something that
could be cost prohibitive.

01:04:41.050 --> 01:04:43.480
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: For us in San
Francisco, we're extremely lucky

01:04:43.480 --> 01:04:47.000
because we've had sheriffs
for the last thirty years

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:51.730
that have concentrated on the
development of re-entry services

01:04:51.730 --> 01:04:53.560
for all prisoners in the jail.

01:04:53.560 --> 01:04:55.510
So, we were able
to tap into a lot

01:04:55.510 --> 01:04:57.940
of already developed programs,

01:04:57.940 --> 01:05:00.210
tailor them specifically
for veterans.

01:05:00.210 --> 01:05:01.820
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: And if you
can do it in San Francisco

01:05:01.820 --> 01:05:04.120
with no extra money, then
it can be done anywhere.

01:05:04.120 --> 01:05:05.420
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: That's correct.

01:05:05.420 --> 01:05:06.720
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Let me
ask you the same question.

01:05:06.720 --> 01:05:10.380
Is this something you're
finding that you can do by just,

01:05:10.380 --> 01:05:12.510
maybe talking to few folks,
redirecting some assets

01:05:12.510 --> 01:05:14.890
and not necessarily putting
more on the budget line?

01:05:14.890 --> 01:05:16.190
&gt;&gt; Captain Malik Muhammad:

01:05:16.190 --> 01:05:17.490
We did exactly the same
thing down in Orlando.

01:05:17.490 --> 01:05:19.740
We were able to start our unit
without using any addition

01:05:19.740 --> 01:05:22.390
or physical resources, because
we had a physical plan --

01:05:22.390 --> 01:05:23.690
space available.

01:05:23.690 --> 01:05:25.450
And we had a good
program in place,

01:05:25.450 --> 01:05:27.120
it was relatively
easy transition.

01:05:27.120 --> 01:05:29.640
So I want to let you guys know
that it's not a hard process,

01:05:29.640 --> 01:05:33.070
and you can do it without
spending a whole lot of money.

01:05:33.070 --> 01:05:34.430
&gt;&gt; Greg Crawford: And I
want to make the point

01:05:34.430 --> 01:05:36.460
that I think the first thing you
ought to do if you're thinking

01:05:36.460 --> 01:05:38.600
about this is identify
your population.

01:05:38.600 --> 01:05:41.120
Find out how many people you
actually have in custody,

01:05:41.120 --> 01:05:45.040
and you know, data will drive
a lot of your decisions, right?

01:05:45.040 --> 01:05:46.340
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Judge,

01:05:46.340 --> 01:05:47.640
do you find that to
be an effective tool?

01:05:47.640 --> 01:05:48.940
&gt;&gt; Judge Michael E. Jackson:
It's exactly the same.

01:05:48.940 --> 01:05:52.780
It was easy to convince -- in
our jurisdiction, I'm a veteran,

01:05:52.780 --> 01:05:55.340
the sheriff is a veteran,
the deputy sheriff who was

01:05:55.340 --> 01:05:56.650
in charge of us is a veteran.

01:05:56.650 --> 01:05:59.090
We both came to this
idea the same time,

01:05:59.090 --> 01:06:00.390
we just weren't working
together.

01:06:00.390 --> 01:06:03.160
We talked to each
other and we started it

01:06:03.160 --> 01:06:06.310
within I think sixty days
after our first meeting.

01:06:06.310 --> 01:06:08.650
It's just reorganizing the jail,

01:06:08.650 --> 01:06:12.590
and finding a spot
that's suitable

01:06:12.590 --> 01:06:14.480
in the confinement facility.

01:06:14.480 --> 01:06:17.570
Training your guards to deal
with veterans differently.

01:06:17.570 --> 01:06:21.260
Many of the sheriff deputies
and the corrections officers

01:06:21.260 --> 01:06:24.400
who are veterans wanted to
participate in this project,

01:06:24.400 --> 01:06:28.010
in the county jail,
because they were veterans.

01:06:28.010 --> 01:06:30.860
Some were upset because
they were doing it.

01:06:30.860 --> 01:06:34.400
But by and large, most of the
veterans wanted to be involved

01:06:34.400 --> 01:06:38.780
because they sensed that
these veterans with some help,

01:06:38.780 --> 01:06:42.130
would be on taking the
first step towards recovery.

01:06:42.130 --> 01:06:44.030
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: And we'll
talk in a second about the kind

01:06:44.030 --> 01:06:46.170
of pitfalls that you might run
into, that might be helpful

01:06:46.170 --> 01:06:48.160
to somebody, maybe somebody
watching live and they have

01:06:48.160 --> 01:06:49.970
like a jurisdiction out there
that they've been thinking

01:06:49.970 --> 01:06:51.270
about it, but haven't done it.

01:06:51.270 --> 01:06:52.850
Let's get to that in a second,
but talk to me for a second

01:06:52.850 --> 01:06:55.360
about the characteristics
of veteran inmate,

01:06:55.360 --> 01:06:56.850
are they a different population?

01:06:56.850 --> 01:07:00.440
Because you have some folks
that are just chronic criminals,

01:07:00.440 --> 01:07:02.770
life-long criminals, and
these people are not going

01:07:02.770 --> 01:07:04.130
to be fixed or cured
of anything.

01:07:04.130 --> 01:07:05.430
Well, when veterans come in,

01:07:05.430 --> 01:07:06.830
do you get the sense
they've just made a mistake,

01:07:06.830 --> 01:07:09.020
they made bad decisions,
they can be put back

01:07:09.020 --> 01:07:12.340
on a path quickly, is it an
easy adjust or what is it?

01:07:12.340 --> 01:07:15.140
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: Veterans
seem to fit

01:07:15.140 --> 01:07:20.490
into a jail setting rather
naturally, because of the fact

01:07:20.490 --> 01:07:26.430
that your jails and prisons
operate some semi-militaristic,

01:07:26.430 --> 01:07:29.530
with inspections, with
line-up's, etcetera,

01:07:29.530 --> 01:07:33.160
with work detailed,
structure, exactly.

01:07:33.160 --> 01:07:39.210
So a veteran coming into the
jail system can fit very easily

01:07:39.210 --> 01:07:41.490
into that system,
and a lot times,

01:07:41.490 --> 01:07:44.190
what we found before we
started our veterans program,

01:07:44.190 --> 01:07:47.310
is the best workers in the
jail that were identified,

01:07:47.310 --> 01:07:50.180
were often veterans, and
veterans who had come back

01:07:50.180 --> 01:07:53.880
into jail, "Oh, there's Gunny,
he's going to run the kitchen."

01:07:53.880 --> 01:07:55.430
We see that quite often.

01:07:55.430 --> 01:07:56.730
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: So
they feel plugged in.

01:07:56.730 --> 01:07:58.210
They feel like they
have a purpose?

01:07:58.210 --> 01:07:59.510
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: Yep.

01:07:59.510 --> 01:08:00.970
They can follow the
orders, they, you know,

01:08:00.970 --> 01:08:03.720
they've got the structure,
get up at a certain time,

01:08:03.720 --> 01:08:06.270
go off to your work
detail, come back,

01:08:06.270 --> 01:08:09.160
here's your phone call
time, here's your meal time,

01:08:09.160 --> 01:08:12.730
here's your nap time,
and so it makes --

01:08:12.730 --> 01:08:15.410
it's much more easier than
the world they were living

01:08:15.410 --> 01:08:17.840
in on the outside where
they lost that structure

01:08:17.840 --> 01:08:19.620
and lost that comradery.

01:08:19.620 --> 01:08:20.920
&gt;&gt; Greg Crawford: Just
something that Jim mentioned

01:08:20.920 --> 01:08:23.080
in his introductory
remarks is reminding them

01:08:23.080 --> 01:08:24.840
of the confidence
that they once had.

01:08:24.840 --> 01:08:27.850
And I think that's an important
point that I think this kind

01:08:27.850 --> 01:08:32.670
of programing does for veterans,
is it kind of gets their sense

01:08:32.670 --> 01:08:34.830
of self, you know, purpose back,

01:08:34.830 --> 01:08:36.130
and I think that
that's what it does.

01:08:36.130 --> 01:08:37.580
It get's their confidence going.

01:08:37.580 --> 01:08:39.350
&gt;&gt; Captain Malik Muhammad:
It kind of reacclimates them,

01:08:39.350 --> 01:08:41.200
back to that military
life, because jails

01:08:41.200 --> 01:08:44.870
and prison are traditionally a
para-military type organization.

01:08:44.870 --> 01:08:46.960
So being in that
environment reacclimates them

01:08:46.960 --> 01:08:49.130
to what they were
once accustomed to.

01:08:49.130 --> 01:08:50.790
Also, by placing
them in position

01:08:50.790 --> 01:08:53.210
to where they're working for the
jails and doing various things,

01:08:53.210 --> 01:08:55.610
it gives them a sense of pride
and a sense of leadership.

01:08:55.610 --> 01:08:57.690
And also, you have
that belongingness

01:08:57.690 --> 01:08:59.060
that they often times seek.

01:08:59.060 --> 01:09:00.830
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: But anytime
we send somebody way to prison,

01:09:00.830 --> 01:09:02.990
the hope is, in the
back of the minds is

01:09:02.990 --> 01:09:05.320
that justice would be served,
that they'll learn their lesson

01:09:05.320 --> 01:09:06.750
and they'll come
back into society.

01:09:06.750 --> 01:09:10.370
Do you get a sense from veterans
when they do make bad decisions,

01:09:10.370 --> 01:09:13.250
find themselves incarcerated
that they are a population

01:09:13.250 --> 01:09:17.820
that is much higher at perhaps
going back and reacclimating

01:09:17.820 --> 01:09:21.130
to public life by learning
something from prison?

01:09:21.130 --> 01:09:22.430
Are they successful

01:09:22.430 --> 01:09:25.320
as candidates coming
out of incarceration?

01:09:25.320 --> 01:09:27.750
I don't know, I'm asking you.

01:09:29.090 --> 01:09:31.070
&gt;&gt; Judge Michael E. Jackson:
Well, in many of the prison's,

01:09:31.070 --> 01:09:35.150
particularly in Ohio, I think
it's pretty much nationwide.

01:09:35.150 --> 01:09:38.360
The veterans in prison
have organized themselves

01:09:38.360 --> 01:09:41.580
and they've been permitted
by prison authorities,

01:09:41.580 --> 01:09:44.970
allowing them to do this, to
set up very similar operations

01:09:44.970 --> 01:09:46.760
than -- as we're talking

01:09:46.760 --> 01:09:49.580
about with the veterans
in the county jail.

01:09:49.580 --> 01:09:52.080
So if you go to a
number of prions in Ohio,

01:09:52.080 --> 01:09:54.930
you'll see a veterans pod there.

01:09:54.930 --> 01:09:59.580
Some of them are even working
towards doing productive

01:09:59.580 --> 01:10:02.550
business while in
prison, it's authorized.

01:10:02.550 --> 01:10:04.560
And they have their
own discipline group

01:10:04.560 --> 01:10:06.250
among themselves.

01:10:06.250 --> 01:10:10.360
And they are transitioning
to the community

01:10:10.360 --> 01:10:11.920
by having people come in.

01:10:11.920 --> 01:10:15.920
In fact, one of the veteran
service organization the AMVETS,

01:10:15.920 --> 01:10:19.870
they even have chapters
of AMVETS

01:10:19.870 --> 01:10:23.420
or like American
Legion, VFW, in prisons.

01:10:23.420 --> 01:10:26.600
And so they are a member
of a veterans organization.

01:10:26.600 --> 01:10:28.510
So it's not as if it
doesn't go on there.

01:10:28.510 --> 01:10:31.120
So hopefully when they
transition out, they'll have

01:10:31.120 --> 01:10:37.410
that foundation that they can
recreate, and live productive

01:10:37.410 --> 01:10:38.710
and law-abiding lives.

01:10:38.710 --> 01:10:43.170
The connection in the jails
also is worthy of note,

01:10:43.170 --> 01:10:45.610
when you connect with a
veteran's treatment court,

01:10:45.610 --> 01:10:49.420
so I would get those people from
the veteran's pod in the jail,

01:10:49.420 --> 01:10:51.830
put them in a veteran's
treatment court program,

01:10:51.830 --> 01:10:54.650
where they have four stages
that hey have to go through.

01:10:54.650 --> 01:10:58.880
And when they graduate, they
have the ability, we hope,

01:10:58.880 --> 01:11:02.300
to be self-sustaining.

01:11:02.300 --> 01:11:03.600
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: What
kinds of mistakes are some

01:11:03.600 --> 01:11:05.670
of these veterans making when
they come back, when they decide

01:11:05.670 --> 01:11:08.050
to make bad decisions and
find themselves incarcerated.

01:11:08.050 --> 01:11:10.570
Because I know we have the
court system that was setup,

01:11:10.570 --> 01:11:11.910
we talked about last year.

01:11:11.910 --> 01:11:14.460
Which tries to kind of intervene
and get in between some

01:11:14.460 --> 01:11:15.760
of those veterans
that are coming back,

01:11:15.760 --> 01:11:17.630
that have just made minor
infractions in the world

01:11:17.630 --> 01:11:19.130
of the criminal justice system.

01:11:19.130 --> 01:11:22.090
Some of this though, I mean,
this are very serious charges

01:11:22.090 --> 01:11:24.040
that they probably will
never see the light of day.

01:11:24.040 --> 01:11:26.780
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: Sometimes it
can be something as simple

01:11:26.780 --> 01:11:30.650
as not being in compliance
with their medication.

01:11:30.650 --> 01:11:37.690
We had an individual that came
into our system, was a captain,

01:11:37.690 --> 01:11:42.170
a rogue scholar, a
West Point graduate.

01:11:42.170 --> 01:11:44.920
When he got out of
the military, he went

01:11:44.920 --> 01:11:48.480
and got himself a little plot
of land in Alaska that butted

01:11:48.480 --> 01:11:52.180
up against the forest, and
everything was fine except

01:11:52.180 --> 01:11:55.060
when he came back to visit
family in the bay area.

01:11:55.060 --> 01:11:58.090
And he got himself
into a situation

01:11:58.090 --> 01:12:02.690
where he should have been
dealt with psychiatrically,

01:12:02.690 --> 01:12:05.620
but instead wound
up being jailed.

01:12:05.620 --> 01:12:09.270
He came to our attention,
we weren't able to get him

01:12:09.270 --> 01:12:11.870
into cover because of
his psychiatric issues,

01:12:11.870 --> 01:12:14.600
but we were able to get
him into veteran's court,

01:12:14.600 --> 01:12:17.330
get him stabilized,
and it was determined

01:12:17.330 --> 01:12:20.510
through veteran's court that
the best thing to do would be

01:12:20.510 --> 01:12:23.670
to get him back to his
community, back into Alaska

01:12:23.670 --> 01:12:27.500
where he had veteran
services already in place.

01:12:27.500 --> 01:12:28.800
We were able to do that.

01:12:28.800 --> 01:12:32.180
We had one of our veteran's
court, mentors fly back

01:12:32.180 --> 01:12:36.490
to Alaska with them, and his
veterans court status has been

01:12:36.490 --> 01:12:38.040
transitioned to Alaska.

01:12:38.040 --> 01:12:40.010
He's still having difficulties,

01:12:40.010 --> 01:12:42.220
but it was the best
place for him.

01:12:42.220 --> 01:12:44.230
And again, he should
never have been

01:12:44.230 --> 01:12:46.450
in the criminal justice
system, he should have been

01:12:46.450 --> 01:12:48.650
in the mental health
system, but got caught

01:12:48.650 --> 01:12:51.190
up in criminal justice.

01:12:51.190 --> 01:12:53.740
But because of the
efforts of having COVER,

01:12:53.740 --> 01:12:58.350
having veterans court, he's
not perfect, but he's stable,

01:12:58.350 --> 01:13:01.570
and he's living day to day.

01:13:01.570 --> 01:13:03.480
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: Sheriff
some of your examples?

01:13:03.480 --> 01:13:04.780
&gt;&gt; Captain Malik Muhammad:
I was going to say that,

01:13:04.780 --> 01:13:06.720
just like the technical
violation that he mentioned.

01:13:06.720 --> 01:13:09.520
Sometime I've seen them come
back for self-medicating,

01:13:09.520 --> 01:13:10.820
if they don't take care

01:13:10.820 --> 01:13:12.160
of the substance abuse issue
while they're in custody

01:13:12.160 --> 01:13:13.790
and get the right treatment.

01:13:13.790 --> 01:13:16.760
Sometimes, when times get
tough when they're realized,

01:13:16.760 --> 01:13:18.770
they tend to self-medicate
and find themselves back

01:13:18.770 --> 01:13:20.250
in custody due to
something as minor as,

01:13:20.250 --> 01:13:22.970
let's say, failing a drug test.

01:13:24.010 --> 01:13:25.310
&gt;&gt; Judge Michael E. Jackson:

01:13:25.310 --> 01:13:27.330
I think all of the veteran
supreme court judges

01:13:27.330 --> 01:13:31.980
and those involved with
helping veterans while in jail,

01:13:31.980 --> 01:13:35.500
all recognize that there
are a number of veterans

01:13:35.500 --> 01:13:38.380
who draw some pretty
serious charges.

01:13:38.380 --> 01:13:41.730
And one of the things that
we have to distinguish is,

01:13:41.730 --> 01:13:44.200
holding those -- that
induvial, veteran or not,

01:13:44.200 --> 01:13:46.690
to be accountable
for their conduct.

01:13:46.690 --> 01:13:50.790
The part that comes into play
that's effective for veterans is

01:13:50.790 --> 01:13:53.210
that to the extent, we can,

01:13:53.210 --> 01:13:57.020
we couple that with a
treatment situation.

01:13:57.020 --> 01:13:58.990
So, I just had a case
a couple of weeks ago,

01:13:58.990 --> 01:14:03.110
where a veteran had a flash
back, he was combat veteran,

01:14:03.110 --> 01:14:05.920
Iraq, had a flashback,
as I mentioned,

01:14:05.920 --> 01:14:08.880
three police officers
were injured.

01:14:08.880 --> 01:14:12.640
None life threatening
to my knowledge.

01:14:12.640 --> 01:14:14.500
The three officers asked for --

01:14:14.500 --> 01:14:16.530
were given the opportunity
at sentencing

01:14:16.530 --> 01:14:19.710
to say what they wanted to
happen to this individual.

01:14:19.710 --> 01:14:21.180
One said, prison.

01:14:21.180 --> 01:14:23.470
One said, judge it's up to you.

01:14:23.470 --> 01:14:26.680
And the other said, most
definitely probation.

01:14:26.680 --> 01:14:31.870
The person who said probation
was a combat veteran.

01:14:31.870 --> 01:14:35.590
And he understood what was
going on with that veteran,

01:14:35.590 --> 01:14:37.960
with regard to a flashback.

01:14:37.960 --> 01:14:42.740
And so as a treatment
court judge, I have to make

01:14:42.740 --> 01:14:44.720
that decision with regard
to being accountable

01:14:44.720 --> 01:14:46.980
to that conduct,
which was serious,

01:14:46.980 --> 01:14:51.420
but also make him
available to the services

01:14:51.420 --> 01:14:53.100
that I think would help him.

01:14:53.100 --> 01:14:55.260
In his situation, he's
going to be confined for up

01:14:55.260 --> 01:14:58.770
to nine months, maybe a little
bit less if he does well.

01:14:58.770 --> 01:15:00.620
But he's going to be in the
veteran's treatment court,

01:15:00.620 --> 01:15:03.510
and he's going to be in the
veteran's pod, and he's going

01:15:03.510 --> 01:15:08.040
to have access to some
treatment during those process.

01:15:08.040 --> 01:15:09.340
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Elias: One
of the biggest issues,

01:15:09.340 --> 01:15:10.640
especially with those
veterans coming back with PTSD,

01:15:10.640 --> 01:15:12.860
especially being in the new
business we're keenly aware,

01:15:12.860 --> 01:15:16.250
this is domestic violence, the
numbers are just astronomical.

01:15:16.250 --> 01:15:18.080
It has to go back -- it
goes back to the language

01:15:18.080 --> 01:15:20.310
that I was discussing earlier
about the language of war

01:15:20.310 --> 01:15:22.250
when you come back, you don't
speak the same language.

01:15:22.250 --> 01:15:24.300
And the language in a
relationship is much different.

01:15:24.300 --> 01:15:26.530
There's an intimate -- an
intimacy with a relationship

01:15:26.530 --> 01:15:27.830
of understanding another person.

01:15:27.830 --> 01:15:29.960
But that side of
veterans, especially those

01:15:29.960 --> 01:15:32.200
who have seen combat, or
they've been affected by war

01:15:32.200 --> 01:15:35.860
in such a meaningful way,
that shuts down in them.

01:15:35.860 --> 01:15:38.330
Breaking through those
communication lines,

01:15:38.330 --> 01:15:39.820
this is one of those
opportunities,

01:15:39.820 --> 01:15:41.120
and unfortunately
it comes to prison,

01:15:41.120 --> 01:15:42.420
and that's what we're talking
about with this setting.

01:15:42.420 --> 01:15:44.960
But in that setting where
you have other veterans,

01:15:44.960 --> 01:15:46.260
they become a support group.

01:15:46.260 --> 01:15:48.760
But it almost -- I think it
breaks everybody's heart hearing

01:15:48.760 --> 01:15:50.690
the fact that they have
to go to prison in other

01:15:50.690 --> 01:15:52.940
to find the support group
that ultimately can help them

01:15:52.940 --> 01:15:54.460
on the road to recovery.

01:15:54.460 --> 01:15:56.050
Is that right?

01:15:56.050 --> 01:15:57.440
&gt;&gt; Judge Michael E.
Jackson: Absolutely.

01:15:57.440 --> 01:16:00.760
I interviewed all 22 people
in our jail, I talked to them,

01:16:00.760 --> 01:16:03.340
I did an interview,
before I came out here,

01:16:03.340 --> 01:16:06.140
and all of them said essentially
the same thing that's

01:16:06.140 --> 01:16:07.860
in our publication.

01:16:07.860 --> 01:16:10.690
They use this as a support
group amongst themselves.

01:16:10.690 --> 01:16:13.200
And so, they really
are helping themselves.

01:16:13.200 --> 01:16:16.220
And one of the veterans came up
to me and said, "You now, judge,

01:16:16.220 --> 01:16:19.230
couple of vets were bad rapping
you, and I had to talk to them."

01:16:19.230 --> 01:16:22.010
I'm not quite sure what he
said to them, but one of them,

01:16:22.010 --> 01:16:25.510
he said, he didn't think
the punishment was right,

01:16:25.510 --> 01:16:27.920
and the other vet said, "Well,

01:16:27.920 --> 01:16:32.400
you have four positive tests
for, you know, drug use.

01:16:32.400 --> 01:16:34.060
What did you expect?"

01:16:34.060 --> 01:16:37.040
So, they can have
that conversation.

01:16:37.040 --> 01:16:39.220
And they can talk it out.

01:16:39.220 --> 01:16:40.520
And whether it's right or wrong,

01:16:40.520 --> 01:16:43.660
or whether my punishment
was too hard or too lean,

01:16:43.660 --> 01:16:47.070
they have an avenue of talking
it out among themselves.

01:16:47.070 --> 01:16:50.460
And they can hear other sides
and that doesn't generally go

01:16:50.460 --> 01:16:54.670
on in the population as I think
many other sheriffs could attest

01:16:54.670 --> 01:16:56.040
better than I.

01:16:56.040 --> 01:16:57.340
&gt;&gt; Ron Perez: And I
just wanted to add,

01:16:57.340 --> 01:16:59.790
you touched on domestic
violence.

01:16:59.790 --> 01:17:03.620
Our program, we have
a component --

01:17:03.620 --> 01:17:06.180
that sheriff's department had
this component quite some time

01:17:06.180 --> 01:17:08.350
ago resolve to stop
the violence,

01:17:08.350 --> 01:17:12.020
and anti-domestic violence,
anti-partner program.

01:17:12.020 --> 01:17:15.760
It's been adopted -- had been
adapted, actually, by the VA

01:17:15.760 --> 01:17:19.800
and is being provided in
San Francisco to veterans,

01:17:19.800 --> 01:17:22.970
and on the outside,
it's called, 'At-Ease'.

01:17:22.970 --> 01:17:27.660
We have a component in our COVER
program, we call it stand down,

01:17:27.660 --> 01:17:31.480
but it talks -- it deals
with the male world --

01:17:31.480 --> 01:17:36.310
belief system and violence,
and addressing that.

01:17:36.310 --> 01:17:39.310
But it's geared toward veterans.

01:17:39.310 --> 01:17:42.230
And I believe it's probably
the first one in the country

01:17:42.230 --> 01:17:45.680
to be started specifically
for veterans on dealing

01:17:45.680 --> 01:17:48.060
with domestic violence,
'cause again, that's something

01:17:48.060 --> 01:17:52.810
that they VA, up until this
point has not been looking at.

01:17:52.810 --> 01:17:57.620
&gt;&gt; Bernie Edelman: You now, it
strikes me that we feel so good

01:17:57.620 --> 01:18:02.560
when folks come back from a tour
of duty whether it is in Iraq,

01:18:02.560 --> 01:18:06.700
Afghanistan, or Vietnam, they
are greeted by their family,

01:18:06.700 --> 01:18:09.640
and it is supposed to be
wonderful at least it is

01:18:09.640 --> 01:18:13.490
in the opinion of the eyes
of people who see that.

01:18:13.490 --> 01:18:16.180
There are an awful lot
of guys who come back,

01:18:16.180 --> 01:18:18.210
they haven't got no family.

01:18:18.210 --> 01:18:19.800
The family is dysfunctional.

01:18:19.800 --> 01:18:22.020
They have been dysfunctional
for years.

01:18:22.020 --> 01:18:26.360
Their family were the
brothers and sisters they had

01:18:26.360 --> 01:18:28.960
in a combat situation.

01:18:28.960 --> 01:18:31.920
All of a sudden,
they find themselves

01:18:31.920 --> 01:18:34.110
without a support group.

01:18:34.110 --> 01:18:36.630
They start drinking or drugging.

01:18:36.630 --> 01:18:40.670
I know of one guy, he was
a crew chief on a medevac,

01:18:40.670 --> 01:18:43.320
a medical evacuation helicopter.

01:18:43.320 --> 01:18:47.140
He would slush through
blood every day

01:18:47.140 --> 01:18:48.960
that he was in the air.

01:18:48.960 --> 01:18:54.670
He came back, couldn't talk,
got married, couldn't talk

01:18:55.770 --> 01:18:59.480
to his wife, upstairs of
a bar, and for10 years,

01:18:59.480 --> 01:19:03.470
he drank himself into
oblivion every night.

01:19:03.470 --> 01:19:06.440
He started having
flashbacks on his way to work

01:19:06.440 --> 01:19:08.500
when he got a different job.

01:19:08.500 --> 01:19:10.230
His life was all but stuck.

01:19:10.230 --> 01:19:14.170
Nobody told him he had
anything wrong with him.

01:19:14.170 --> 01:19:16.560
He knew there was
something the matter,

01:19:16.560 --> 01:19:19.120
but he didn't know what it was.

01:19:19.120 --> 01:19:22.590
We took a long time before
there was an intervention

01:19:22.590 --> 01:19:26.680
and he started getting health
[inaudible] and one of that is

01:19:26.680 --> 01:19:28.400
through the vet centers,
which were one

01:19:28.400 --> 01:19:34.040
of the most successful
operations of the VA.

01:19:34.040 --> 01:19:38.610
We [inaudible] of
the VA to keep that.

01:19:38.610 --> 01:19:40.600
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
So, talking about, you know,

01:19:40.600 --> 01:19:45.990
I wish there was some way
to improve from active duty

01:19:45.990 --> 01:19:47.550
to the VA Services,
there is a gap.

01:19:47.550 --> 01:19:50.080
I hate that sometimes with the
first opportunity to intervene

01:19:50.080 --> 01:19:52.740
in someone's life is involvement
with the justice system.

01:19:52.740 --> 01:19:55.390
So, one of the things
that I am really--

01:19:55.390 --> 01:19:58.380
this publication folks is on
housing units for local jails,

01:19:58.380 --> 01:20:00.450
and if you think about the
continuum of criminal justice

01:20:00.450 --> 01:20:02.240
between the community
and law enforcement,

01:20:02.240 --> 01:20:04.680
jails and vet courts,
and prison and re-entry.

01:20:04.680 --> 01:20:05.980
I think what is really
important,

01:20:05.980 --> 01:20:07.320
even though this
publication focuses

01:20:07.320 --> 01:20:10.030
on housing units it also
promotes collaboration

01:20:10.030 --> 01:20:12.810
between entities within the
criminal justice system.

01:20:12.810 --> 01:20:14.730
I think what is really
important for us to think

01:20:14.730 --> 01:20:18.030
about is people are considering
implementing these programs

01:20:18.030 --> 01:20:21.390
as partnering with other parts
of the criminal justice system

01:20:21.390 --> 01:20:24.120
because you can not
only share resources

01:20:24.120 --> 01:20:27.780
but you can improve outcomes
if law enforcement is talking

01:20:27.780 --> 01:20:30.770
to the vet court and that is
something that I have seen

01:20:30.770 --> 01:20:33.860
on the newest project
that we are working

01:20:33.860 --> 01:20:36.990
on around law enforcement
officers responding to veterans

01:20:36.990 --> 01:20:39.850
in crisis overseeing
a sheriff, detective,

01:20:39.850 --> 01:20:42.860
or a detective assigned to a
vet court, and there is a link

01:20:42.860 --> 01:20:46.300
between the housing unit, the
vet court, and the community,

01:20:46.300 --> 01:20:50.300
and I think Judge Jackson has
done a good job of communicating

01:20:50.300 --> 01:20:51.690
between the local jail
and his vet court.

01:20:51.690 --> 01:20:52.990
He was instrumental
in setting that up,

01:20:52.990 --> 01:20:54.380
but I think that that is
something that is important

01:20:54.380 --> 01:20:57.520
to think about is not just
focusing on your own peace

01:20:57.520 --> 01:20:58.820
but look branching out

01:20:58.820 --> 01:21:00.630
and communicating
within your system.

01:21:00.630 --> 01:21:01.930
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
I think most who are going

01:21:01.930 --> 01:21:03.710
to hear this has said this is
a great idea in kind of one

01:21:03.710 --> 01:21:05.010
of those no brainers in life.

01:21:05.010 --> 01:21:07.780
The question I have is why
wouldn't every correctional

01:21:07.780 --> 01:21:11.960
house, whether it's a
small local jurisdiction

01:21:11.960 --> 01:21:13.260
or even a big federal unit,

01:21:13.260 --> 01:21:14.900
why wouldn't they
institute this kind

01:21:14.900 --> 01:21:16.450
of program and do it right away.

01:21:16.450 --> 01:21:18.640
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
I can't really think

01:21:18.640 --> 01:21:20.630
of a reason why they wouldn't,
but I can share with you

01:21:20.630 --> 01:21:22.330
from experience that
when starting up,

01:21:22.330 --> 01:21:24.120
the hardest thing
is just getting buy

01:21:24.120 --> 01:21:26.930
in from the stakeholders
that currently work there,

01:21:26.930 --> 01:21:28.810
the public, and your
administration.

01:21:28.810 --> 01:21:30.940
Those are kind of your hurdles
when you are initially trying

01:21:30.940 --> 01:21:34.280
to start a program and once
you get those accomplished

01:21:34.280 --> 01:21:36.960
or over those three hurdles, I
think it is a little bit easier,

01:21:36.960 --> 01:21:39.150
but again I can't really
think of a reason why

01:21:39.150 --> 01:21:41.610
that we wouldn't look
at helping veterans.

01:21:41.610 --> 01:21:45.070
I say that because not
just because I am a veteran

01:21:45.070 --> 01:21:47.830
but at some point, those men and
women that may be in the units

01:21:47.830 --> 01:21:50.670
that are [inaudible]
uniform, they wore a uniform

01:21:50.670 --> 01:21:53.150
and they decided at some point
they were going to protect us

01:21:53.150 --> 01:21:55.050
and I think for that
we still owe them.

01:21:55.050 --> 01:21:56.350
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
That is such a great point.

01:21:56.350 --> 01:21:57.650
I just want to quickly
point out that

01:21:57.650 --> 01:21:59.850
if you are running a vet court

01:21:59.850 --> 01:22:02.120
or you are running a housing
unit, it's really important

01:22:02.120 --> 01:22:06.740
that you track data-- that you
justify why this programming is

01:22:06.740 --> 01:22:08.040
so important.

01:22:08.040 --> 01:22:10.050
We all know anecdotally
that these programs work

01:22:10.050 --> 01:22:11.930
and they are effective in that
we are reducing [inaudible],

01:22:11.930 --> 01:22:14.900
but if you are listening out
there and you are in charge

01:22:14.900 --> 01:22:17.130
of your dataset, make
sure you are tracking this

01:22:17.130 --> 01:22:18.430
and reporting it back

01:22:18.430 --> 01:22:19.730
and letting us know
how effective these are

01:22:19.730 --> 01:22:21.030
so we can keep building it.

01:22:21.030 --> 01:22:22.630
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker: Let me
ask you as a general population,

01:22:22.630 --> 01:22:25.250
how well do veterans do if,

01:22:25.250 --> 01:22:27.010
let's say this program
didn't exist,

01:22:27.010 --> 01:22:29.570
nobody was instituting
it, and you start veteran

01:22:29.570 --> 01:22:30.870
with a minor infraction

01:22:30.870 --> 01:22:34.040
in general population,
what happens to them?

01:22:35.780 --> 01:22:37.080
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
From what I have read

01:22:37.080 --> 01:22:39.720
and from what I have discussed
with folks and interviewed,

01:22:39.720 --> 01:22:44.680
again in general
population, they don't do well

01:22:44.680 --> 01:22:47.010
because there is no
support system there.

01:22:47.010 --> 01:22:48.610
They don't want to fight
without the guys [inaudible]

01:22:48.610 --> 01:22:51.680
because you want
to fight with them.

01:22:51.680 --> 01:22:54.870
You need to have something
where you can depend on someone

01:22:54.870 --> 01:22:58.170
where you can watch his six
and he can watch your six.

01:22:58.170 --> 01:23:01.170
It doesn't happen in gen pop.

01:23:01.170 --> 01:23:02.610
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
And if they come

01:23:02.610 --> 01:23:06.730
into general population and
don't receive any services,

01:23:06.730 --> 01:23:09.250
they are going to leave
without any services

01:23:09.250 --> 01:23:11.830
and without any direction
and they are probably going

01:23:11.830 --> 01:23:16.020
to be back very, very shortly
or at least with a program

01:23:16.020 --> 01:23:19.910
such as this you are at least
making them aware what services

01:23:19.910 --> 01:23:22.010
are available, you
are making them aware

01:23:22.010 --> 01:23:24.960
of what benefits they are
eligible for because a lot

01:23:24.960 --> 01:23:29.010
of times you will find that
the veteran doesn't realize

01:23:29.010 --> 01:23:30.520
that he is eligible for any.

01:23:30.520 --> 01:23:32.420
Veterans, especially
if they have less

01:23:32.420 --> 01:23:33.810
than an honorable discharge,

01:23:33.810 --> 01:23:36.570
they think that there is
nothing available to them

01:23:36.570 --> 01:23:37.900
when that is not true.

01:23:37.900 --> 01:23:39.200
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker: Let
us talk about the pitfalls

01:23:39.200 --> 01:23:40.570
because there are some
jurisdictions probably,

01:23:40.570 --> 01:23:42.170
after watching right now,
saying, oh, I would love

01:23:42.170 --> 01:23:45.020
to do it, but this is
going to be a hurdle.

01:23:45.020 --> 01:23:47.270
Talk to me about some of the
issues that sort of stood

01:23:47.270 --> 01:23:48.990
in the way that you
quickly overcame

01:23:48.990 --> 01:23:51.710
and how you overcame
those pitfalls?

01:23:51.710 --> 01:23:53.070
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
The biggest issue

01:23:53.070 --> 01:23:55.650
for us was probably
classifications.

01:23:55.650 --> 01:23:58.040
Getting classifications on board

01:23:58.040 --> 01:24:02.290
because obviously
classifications is a real key

01:24:02.290 --> 01:24:05.260
part of it because
they determine whether

01:24:05.260 --> 01:24:09.400
or not the individual
has any gang history,

01:24:09.400 --> 01:24:12.070
what his sophistication
is, and a lot of times

01:24:12.070 --> 01:24:15.830
that is how an individual
is housed, and for a veteran

01:24:15.830 --> 01:24:17.960
if he has got some
things in his background

01:24:17.960 --> 01:24:20.640
that could exclude
him programming.

01:24:20.640 --> 01:24:24.520
So, if you have classifications
on board,

01:24:24.520 --> 01:24:27.170
they know that it is a veteran,
you could look at that veteran

01:24:27.170 --> 01:24:33.100
on a case by case basis, why
did you have these gang ties,

01:24:33.100 --> 01:24:37.060
can you put those gang ties off
to the side, are you willing

01:24:37.060 --> 01:24:39.560
to participate in treatment.

01:24:39.560 --> 01:24:41.690
And for us in California,

01:24:41.690 --> 01:24:44.470
now they have what is
called milestones credits,

01:24:44.470 --> 01:24:48.740
so whether you are in county
jail, whether you are in prison,

01:24:48.740 --> 01:24:52.890
for your participation and
any treatment or any type

01:24:52.890 --> 01:24:55.230
of programming that is
going to give you time off

01:24:55.230 --> 01:24:57.800
of your sentence,
so that is another.

01:24:57.800 --> 01:24:59.100
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:

01:24:59.100 --> 01:25:00.400
Lets quickly get
some thoughts shared.

01:25:00.400 --> 01:25:01.700
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker: I was
just going to say just getting

01:25:01.700 --> 01:25:03.460
by in from the staff there
unless you want to start

01:25:03.460 --> 01:25:06.810
in the program depending on
the number of veterans you have

01:25:06.810 --> 01:25:09.430
in your organization to
get some form of push back.

01:25:09.430 --> 01:25:10.850
That pushback can be in the form

01:25:10.850 --> 01:25:12.460
of some veterans
actually thought

01:25:12.460 --> 01:25:14.100
about establishing
a housing unit

01:25:14.100 --> 01:25:16.380
that would somehow
diminish their service.

01:25:16.380 --> 01:25:18.470
Once you do buy in and
do training with them,

01:25:18.470 --> 01:25:20.240
they quickly realize that
there are some benefits

01:25:20.240 --> 01:25:24.470
in there of having a program.

01:25:24.470 --> 01:25:28.870
&gt;&gt; Judge Jackson: I think the
staff issue is the main thing,

01:25:28.870 --> 01:25:31.460
training the staff, making
sure they understand it,

01:25:31.460 --> 01:25:34.580
and also convincing
people outside community

01:25:34.580 --> 01:25:36.460
and inside the jail facility

01:25:36.460 --> 01:25:38.570
that these veterans are
not getting a break.

01:25:38.570 --> 01:25:43.190
They are being put
together because, one,

01:25:43.190 --> 01:25:49.850
there is less problem, less
time they are going to be spent

01:25:49.850 --> 01:25:53.890
in confinement and reduced
privileges and you are going

01:25:53.890 --> 01:25:58.300
to have necessary fewer guards
involved in guarding these vets.

01:25:58.300 --> 01:26:03.890
So, there is an advantage that
can be assessed that will be

01:26:03.890 --> 01:26:09.100
of benefit to the veterans
and to the jail facility.

01:26:10.540 --> 01:26:12.220
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
I think for anybody

01:26:12.220 --> 01:26:16.340
